<HEAD>Voinovich In Governor's Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Voinovich </PERSON> entered the 1990 governor's race Thursday, promising <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> the same leadership that he said made <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> a municipal success story over the past decade. `` <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> is off of the rocks and on a roll. Our neighborhoods are better, our jobs are up and the jokes are down,'' said <PERSON> Voinovich </PERSON>, an unsuccesful 1988 Republican <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> candidate, one-time lieutenant governor, former state representative and <LOCATION> Cuyahoga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> auditor. <PERSON> Voinovich </PERSON>, 52, brushed aside questions about his defeat in the Sentate race last year by Democratic Sen. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, whom <PERSON> Voinovich </PERSON> accused during the campaign of being soft on child pornography. <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> Chairman, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruvolo </PERSON>, revived past complaints of negative campaigning by <PERSON> Voinovich </PERSON> against <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> last fall and said he wishes the mayor `` the same success he had last year.'' Gov. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Celeste </PERSON>, a Democrat, is barred by the state constitution from seeking a third consecutive term.
