<HEAD>Report: Iraq Downed Egyptian Jet By Mistake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An Iraqi soldier shot down an Egyptian jet fighter by mistake last week as it descended to land in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> for an air show, a published report here said. The two Egyptian fliers ejected safely before the plane crashed, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported in Friday's editions. The Iraqi government had invited <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> to fly its home-built Alpha fighter-bomber to <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> for the air show, but apparently word of the invitation had not reached the soldier who, armed with shoulder-fired missile, downed the unfamiliar jet, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said. The newspaper cited secret intelligence reports making the rounds of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government offices here as the source of the story. The Alpha jet was developed by French and German aircraft firms. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> has purchased Alpha kits from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and assembles the fighter-bomber in a plant south of <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>. The jet has a top speed of 600 mph. Two years ago, in another case of mistaken identity, an Iraqi pilot in a Mirage F1 bomber shot two Exocet missiles into the USS Stark, killing 37 sailors aboard the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> frigate in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. Iraqi officials said the pilot mistook the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ship for an Iranian vessel. Also, the USS Vincennes downed an Iranian Airbus on July 3, 1988, killing 290 people, as it flew over the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> where <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ships were protecting neutral ships during the Iran-Iraq war. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> said it attempted repeatedly to contact the plane for identification, and when it got no response, the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> destroyed the plane with a surface-to-air missile.
