<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Mister Rogers,0871</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miniseries Making Neighborhood Debut</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PG5 Sent April 26.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The miniseries comes to `` Mister <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>' Neighborhood'' next week, and the show's cardigan-clad creator promises a message as gentle and reassuring as ever The three-part musical, titled `` <PERSON> Josephine </PERSON> the Short-Neck Giraffe,'' tells the story of a young giraffe who yearns for a long, graceful neck like all the other giraffes. She eventually grows, <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> confided, `` not on the outside, but on the important side.'' `` It's very much like the usual message of the Neighborhood, that you can be acceptable as you are,'' he said, smiling. `` It's not so much the outsides of us that are important. A song sung by <PERSON> Josephine </PERSON> and her friend <PERSON> Hazel </PERSON> the elephant sums it up best, according to <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION>. `` You're much more than a neck, <PERSON> Josephine </PERSON>. And you're much more than a trunk, <PERSON> Hazel </PERSON>. A chicken's more than a peck, and there's more than a smell to a skunk,'' <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> quietly sang during an interview at <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>'s WQED-TV, home to his children's programs for the past 35 years. The special week of new programs gets under way Monday on <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> stations with a trip to the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wild </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Animal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, where viewers are introduced to real-life giraffes and elephants. On Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> visits a film processing lab to have his animal photographs developed. The miniseries, which features a cast of 15, elaborate animal costumes and five sets, runs Wednesday through Friday. <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> gently guides his young audience from one day to the next, summarizing the main events and hinting at what might lie ahead for <PERSON> Josephine </PERSON>. In the Neighborhood of Make-Believe, where animals sing, dance and play the trombone, <PERSON> Josephine </PERSON> is befriended by <PERSON> J.R. </PERSON>, a shy giraffe who overcomes his problems by helping <PERSON> Josephine </PERSON> conquer hers. He accomplishes that with help from <PERSON> Hazel </PERSON> the elephant, who advises him to `` just let your heart speak.'' `` There is n't a time that I see the scene in which <PERSON> J.R. </PERSON> talks and sings with <PERSON> Josephine </PERSON> ... that I have n't gotten chills up my spine,'' <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> said, tapping his right hand against his back. `` And this is something I've worked with for years. There's something so redemptive about someone who is trying so hard to help somebody else. <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION>, 61, wrote `` <PERSON> Josephine </PERSON> the Short-Neck Giraffe'' for a French class assignment at <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Rollins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in 1950. He named <PERSON> J.R. </PERSON> the giraffe after fraternity brother <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Reardon </PERSON>, who went on to sing with the Metropolitan Opera and was a frequent guest on `` Mister Rogers Neighborhood.'' <PERSON> Reardon </PERSON> died a year ago, and the miniseries is dedicated to him. <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> set the story to music in the late 1950s, and about 1,000 records were pressed. Writer <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Head </PERSON> transformed `` <PERSON> Josephine </PERSON> the Short-Neck Giraffe'' into a poem for children in 1975. For years, <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> tried to have the musical produced on stage or as an animated film. `` I still think it would be great for animation and a stage production,'' he said. `` But I thought unless we get it out on the air, I do n't think anybody's going to know about it.'' The story <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> wrote 39 years ago is vastly different from the musical airing next week. It is the Neighborhood's 13th musical. `` At the end of the -LRB- original -RRB- story, when people are telling <PERSON> Josephine </PERSON> that they like her just the way she is, she raises her head to look at them because she has n't really heard this message before and her neck starts to grow. And it grows and grows and grows until her neck is as tall as everybody else's,'' <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> said. In the musical, <PERSON> Josephine </PERSON>'s neck remains short. `` I think it shows how much we've grown,'' <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> said. `` You know, you do n't have to look like everybody else to be acceptable and to feel acceptable. And wishes do n't always come true. `` Because for a year and a day I've been wishing, she sang. That was one of her first songs. Her wish was for a longer neck, she thought. But really her wish was to have people like her exactly as she is. So often what we say we're wishing for is n't necessarily what is behind the wish. This is very philosophical.'' Will pre-schoolers be able to grasp such a serious message, even in such a light-hearted setting? `` Maybe not in words, but let their hearts speak to them the way <PERSON> Hazel </PERSON> said to <PERSON> J.R. </PERSON>, ` Just let your heart speak,''' <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> said. `` I think that that's the way an awful lot of communication takes place.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Elsewhere in television: REAL-LIFE DRAMAS _ <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> has scheduled the made-for-TV movie about the real-life rescue of little <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> <PERSON> McClure </PERSON> from a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> well for May 21. <PERSON> Beau </PERSON> <PERSON> Bridges </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Hingle </PERSON>, <PERSON> Roxana </PERSON> <PERSON> Zal </PERSON> and <PERSON> Patty </PERSON> <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> star. ... Production is set to begin on `` The Preppy Murder,'' a two-hour `` docudrama'' for <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> about the case of <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON> who was convicted in the death of <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> following what he said was an accident during `` rough sex'' in Central Park. The movie will air sometime later this season.
