<FIRST>r i PM-China-Notebook     04-28 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Notebook,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reporter's Notebook: Students March To `Frere Jacques'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Frere Jacques'' never sounded so revolutionary. `` Lying to the people, lying to the people, very strange, very strange,'' hundreds of students sang in place of the usual lyrics of the French children's song. Unlike American anti-Vietnam War marchers of the 1960s, who were serenaded by a generation of rock and folk singers, thousands of Chinese students who marched for democracy have a limited repertoire of marching songs. Most of the time they stick to the national anthem, with its stirring call to the masses to `` arise,'' or the Internationale, the theme song of the international communist movement. But they mix it up a bit with `` Frere Jacques'' and the nursery rhyme `` Baa Baa Black Sheep.'' Only the words were different. `` We did n't have time to write our own songs,'' said one student leader. `` Besides, it's easier to sing when you know the tune.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Police kept their cool but some lost their hats and shoes in skirmishes with students who pushed through their lines toward <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>. When the dust settled after the students pushed through the first line of police, one officer was seen wandering around in his socks, wailing, `` My shoes, my shoes.'' An old woman finally found one of his black cloth shoes and returned it. A student later produced another. In the final standoff before students surged into Tiananmen Square, one worker snatched the hat off an officer's head and tossed it into the crowd. Someone caught it and tossed it back like a frisbee. The officer's arms were linked with his comrades to form a human barricade, so a student politely plunked it back on the policeman's head
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is a model to many of the students. One student described <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaobang </PERSON>, the ousted <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader whose death sparked the recent protests, as `` <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>.'' Another said American student protests in the 1960s against the Vietnam War inspired him and his classmates to take to the streets, despite the fact that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> at that time was <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s Enemy No 1. The question most often asked by students was: `` Do n't <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> students demonstrate, too?''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 The first thing the people noticed was the tinkling of a bell, then a shaved head and finally a gray robe. A <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monk had come to the demonstration. Walking slowly, shaking his prayer bell, the monk blessed the crowd, which parted before him. `` I feel in my heart for you, all of us support you,'' he said. `` Religion has suffered much in this country. I had to thank you for supporting freedom.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Many of the bystanders carried cameras, anxious for souvenirs of the rare day. But good views were hard to get in the constantly moving crowd, forcing some dedicated photographers to climb trees and bus stop signs. One middle-aged man handed his camera to a youth standing on a bicycle and pleaded with him to `` snap the whole roll.'' The roof of one shanty crumbled under the weight of camera-happy spectators and they came crashing down in a cloud of dust. The crowd roared with laughter and nobody seemed hurt.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Most of the police who withdrew in the face of the huge, insistent crowd did so gracefully. About 50 police who had been roughly pushing back bystanders on a side street abruptly formed a line and trotted off down the street. The crowd shouted, `` Thank you'' and surged forward. A few traffic police caught up in the melee simply took off their uniform white cross-chest straps and belts, climbed over a fence and melted into the crowd. Other police crouched on their haunches at the side of the road, heads in their hands, and smiled wearily as the crowd passed.
</TEXT>
