<FIRST>r a PM-FusionFollowup     04-28 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion Followup,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Another Scientist Sees Evidence of Possible Cold Fusion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new experiment confirms observations from the controversial cold fusion research announced last month, giving `` very encouraging'' evidence for fusion, a scientist says. The new experiment generated more power than it consumed and showed two other signs of possible fusion, said researcher <PERSON> Uziel </PERSON> <PERSON> Landau </PERSON>. But results so far are only preliminary and `` we stop short of saying that we see fusion,'' said <PERSON> Landau </PERSON>, a professor of chemical engineering at <ORGANIZATION> Case </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>. Fusion is the nuclear reaction that powers the sun, and some scientists hope to harness it as an environmentally benign power source. It occurs when the cores of two hydrogen atoms fuse. Last month, researchers announced at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> that they had produced fusion at room temperature with a simple apparatus. Conventional fusion research uses extremely high temperatures and complex machinery. Since the announcement, some scientists have reported similar results while others said their attempts to confirm the work failed. <PERSON> Landau </PERSON> worked with two large test tubes, each containing a small palladium rod to act as one electrode, and a titanium-coated platinum mesh to serve as the other. The electrodes were placed in a bath of so-called heavy water, in which hydrogen is replaced by a chemical cousin called deuterium. The liquid also contained lithium, <PERSON> Landau </PERSON> said Thursday in an interview. According to proponents of cold fusion, the reaction occurs in one of the electrodes when current is applied. <PERSON> Landau </PERSON> said his apparatus produced three possible signs of fusion. One was that the apparatus gave off 8 percent to 30 percent more power than it consumed, with the output given off as heat, he said. The apparatus also produced bursts of extremely tiny particles called neutrons. And the heavy water solution showed about a doubling of its initial concentration of tritium, which is a form of hydrogen, <PERSON> Landau </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Landau </PERSON> said he did not test for production of helium, a product of fusion. Future experiments will use ordinary water rather than heavy water, <PERSON> Landau </PERSON> said. Scientists say that can help rule out the possibility that a chemical reaction, rather than a nuclear reaction, produced the experimental results.
</TEXT>
