<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Politics-Glance     04-28 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Politics-Glance,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Government Structure At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Politics, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is an outline of the structure of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and government: PARTY STRUCTURE: The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> holds political power in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, but President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has proposed changes that allow some contested elections to form a legislature that may exercise significant political power. The Communist Party's power is centered in the Politburo and the Secretariat of the party's <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, which has 5,000 elected members, is supposed to be the party's supreme organ, and ordinarily meets every five years. The congress elects the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, made up of 250 to 300 of the country's top leaders. It now has 251 members. The Central Committee normally meets about twice a year to approve policies and formally elects the members of the Politburo and the Secretariat, the two highest party bodies. Since March 11, 1985, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> been general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, head of the Secretariat and leading member of the Politburo. Since Oct. 1, 1988, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> also has been the nation's president, holding top party and government jobs
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 The Secretariat: This Communist Party body is responsible for running social and economic spheres as well as party personnel and ideology, and wields tremendous power over implementation of policy. Politburo membership and a seat on the secretariat traditionally have been considered necessary to gain the top party job. There are now 10 secretaries, including <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 The Politburo: <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> runs meetings of the Politburo, the party's most powerful body. It now has 12 full members and eight candidate, or non-voting, members. The Politburo normally meets every week.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 GOVERNMENT STRUCTURE: The Supreme Soviet: The 1,500 members are elected from a single slate of approved candidates and theoretically make up the top government body in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. But it has traditionally met only twice a year to ratify policy set by the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Under a reform pushed through by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, the Supreme Soviet will become a smaller body _ with about 500 members _ that meets several months a year. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> says he wants it to be more active, handling operational questions the party apparatus has assumed over the years and leaving the party to decide policy questions. But the Supreme Soviet has not met under the new format, and the extent of its powers is uncertain. The Presidium of the Supreme Soviet: The presidium, which has 37 members, is the collective presidency that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> leads as chairman. Presidents of each of the 15 Soviet republics are members. The presidium has the power to issue government decrees when the Supreme Soviet, or parliament, is not in session. But the presence of Politburo and regional party leaders in its membership ensures its actions have prior top-level approval.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Council of Ministers: The council, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s Cabinet, is responsible for day-to-day operation of government ministries such as agriculture or transportation. It is headed by Premier <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON>, a full member of the Politburo.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 CONGRESS OF PEOPLES DEPUTIES: The <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peoples </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION> is a new 2,250-member body consisting of 1,500 deputies elected from geographical organizations and 750 elected from the party and its affiliates, social, professional and trade union organizations. The congress, which was elected in the first multicandidate balloting, is empowered to choose the president and the Supreme Soviet from among its members, amend the constitution, and review the president's choice for premier.
</TEXT>
