<HEAD>The Loneliest Diplomat in Town?</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ostracized by the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, confined to the city limits, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s top diplomat in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> leads a frustrating existence. <LOCATION> Miagol </LOCATION> _ the first, last and only name of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s charge d'affaires _ is hoping the recent pullout of 115,000 Soviet troops from his country will ease some of the isolation imposed on him by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. But he is also realistic. The Soviet-educated economist invited Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> to his embassy's reception Thursday evening marking the 11th anniversary of the revolution that brought to power a Marxist-oriented government and resulted in the 1979 Soviet invasion. `` They said he could n't come, unfortunately,'' <PERSON> Miagol </PERSON> said with a skeptical laugh. Very few Americans attended the reception, which drew mostly diplomats from Soviet bloc and other communist and socialist countries. For a man who has to ask permission every time he wants to leave the city _ and is usually turned down _ <PERSON> Miagol </PERSON> was remarkably cheerful at an interview in the resplendent red-brick mansion which doubles as residence and embassy. `` Physically our life is good,'' he said, `` but morale is difficult.'' <PERSON> Miagol </PERSON>, one of 15 children, does not know how old he is but estimates his age at about 40. `` My mother said there was snow on the ground, but she did n't know in what year,'' he said. <PERSON> Miagol </PERSON> arrived here 10 months ago with his <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> wife and two children. When he asked to travel to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> by car to attend the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> meetings of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> last fall, he was told to go by plane. When he asked permission to drive to the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>'s recreation compound outside <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, he was denied `` They said it was too far. But people from other socialist embassies also have 25-mile limit, and they are allowed to go,'' <PERSON> Miagol </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other countries impose 25-mile travel limits on diplomats from countries deemed unfriendly. `` This makes me nervous,'' <PERSON> Miagol </PERSON> said. He spends his days reading messages received by telex from <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, dealing with administrative matters relating to his three-man embassy and keeping in touch with the extensive community of Afghan exiles in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. His only contact with the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is through <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gookin </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Protocol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, whom he sees about twice a month. `` I give him my opinions,'' <PERSON> Miagol </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Gookin </PERSON> listens politely _ `` he's a very nice man'' _ and conveys <PERSON> Miagol </PERSON>'s views to <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> experts. But <PERSON> Gookin </PERSON> refused to accept a written message from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s leader <PERSON> Najibullah </PERSON> congratulating <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on his inauguration as president and expressing his hopes for improved relations, <PERSON> Miagol </PERSON> said. `` They told me to put the envelope in a window for letters'' at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, he said. <PERSON> Miagol </PERSON> said he used the same window to deliver a second message several weeks ago asking the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to stop arming the <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> rebels. The rebels, backed by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, fought the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> occupation for nine years and are now locked in a civil war with <PERSON> Najibullah </PERSON>'s Soviet-backed government. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> continues to view <PERSON> Najibullah </PERSON> as a hardline Marxist and fails to see that he is gaining acceptance by Afghans as the only viable choice for leading the war-wracked country, <PERSON> Miagol </PERSON> said. `` They must learn from the mistakes of the Soviets, who did n't understand the Afghan people,'' <PERSON> Miagol </PERSON> said Neither the Soviets nor the Americans understand that Afghans can not embrace Marxism, he said. `` It is not right with our culture, with our religion,'' said the Soviet-educated Moslem. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> withheld recognition from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s government after the Soviets invaded, contending it was not elected democratically and does not represent the Afghan people However, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> continued to function in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, serving as a listening post in the Soviet-run country. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> recognizes many governments that are not democratic, that are fascist dictatorships,'' <PERSON> Miagol </PERSON> said. At least <PERSON> Najibullah </PERSON> was elected to office _ `` maybe not like <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> elections,'' but in accordance with <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s constitution, he said. Once, the Soviets were considered the bad guys in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and the Americans were the good guys, <PERSON> Miagol </PERSON> said. Now, the Soviet tanks and troops have left and they are sending wheat, flour and oil, while the Americans send missiles to the Mujahedeen. `` If the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> continues this, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> will of course be pro-Soviet,'' <PERSON> Miagol </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
