<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Military,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kremlin Will Publish Defense and Space Spending Data, Scientist Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Kremlin will publish long-promised figures on the Soviet defense and space budgets by the end of the year, says <PERSON> Roald </PERSON> <PERSON> Sagdeyev </PERSON>, a leading <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> rocket scientist who is prominent in the reform movement. Soviet military spending is being cut 1.5 percent this year, far short of the 14.2 percent cut announced by Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in January, said <PERSON> Sagdeyev </PERSON>, who is a member of the Supreme Soviet, or parliament. Defense spending will go down another 7 percent in 1990, and the cuts will reach 14.2 percent the following year, he said, although the total amount of the cuts remained unclear. `` We have promised that the absolute figure would be given in the fall,'' <PERSON> Sagdeyev </PERSON> told a group of reporters Thursday. <PERSON> Sagdeyev </PERSON> declined to specify how he knew that military spending figures would be disclosed by year end, but he is thought to be part of a group of scientists and intellectuals who advise <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> on foreign policy. <PERSON> Sagdeyev </PERSON> was also elected in balloting March 26 to represent the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> in the newly created <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peoples </ORGANIZATION>' Deputies, which will have the twin functions of electing a <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> president _ almost certainly voting <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> a new five-year term _ and selecting a new smaller parliament. The issue of Soviet military spending is murky. For years, Western analysts have complained that figures for Soviet defense spending were distorted because prices are set by the state, and the cost of expensive armaments could be vastly underestimated in official statistics. An indefinite delay in implementing price deregulation has led Western analysts to say that even more complete disclosure of Soviet military spending can not be accurate, since Soviet leaders themselves do not know the true cost of weapons. A study released last weekend by the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said that Soviet military spending had risen by 3 percent in 1988. The <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> found strong evidence, however, that last year `` <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> took several actions that evidently were intended to lay the groundwork for future military cuts.'' Furthermore, the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> concluded, the 14.2 percent cut in military spending announced by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> last January probably will lead to much larger cuts than the 500,000 troop reduction he announced at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> last December. <PERSON> Sagdeyev </PERSON>'s description of the 14.2 percent defense cuts as gradual suggested that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> wants to make them as part of arms control agreements with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sagdeyev </PERSON>, in a wide-ranging discussion, also released the text of a hitherto undisclosed resolution he said was passed by the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> last week describing the deaths of 20 demonstrators in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> as a `` criminal act'' that endangered to Kremlin reforms. <PERSON> Sagdeyev </PERSON> was one of three members of the Soviet academy, along with human rights activist <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> historian <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Likhachev </PERSON>, appointed to a parliamentary investigating panel. `` The tragic events in <LOCATION> Tbilisi </LOCATION> -LRB- capital of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> -RRB- confirm the sad fact that perestroika is in danger,'' said the resolution, using the Russian name for <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms. Special uniformed troops under the Soviet <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, or MVD, were responsible for using poisonous chemicals, shovels and clubs to suppress the demonstrations in <LOCATION> Tbilisi </LOCATION> on April 9, killing 20 people, the statement said. `` This unusually cruel act has evoked the deep indignation and outrage of our entire society,'' said the resolution, which <PERSON> Sagdeyev </PERSON> said was passed at a meeting of the entire <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> April 21.
