<FIRST>r a PM-Shuttle-GraphicLaunch     04-28 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle-Graphic Launch,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlantis Astronauts Rely on New Graphics-Oriented Monitors</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>, designing systems in which three or four seconds `` is forever,'' has developed a graphics-oriented computer program to help flight controllers react to launch emergencies. Atlantis, with five astronauts aboard, was scheduled to launch at midafternoon today. In the seconds and minutes after liftoff, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> is to make its most extensive use of a flight control system which highlights potential hazards with colorful displays. Past mission managers had to sort through mind-numbing columns of data on black-and-white monitors that date back to the Gemini era of the 1960s. The new system, inaugurated at <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> after the 1986 Challenger disaster, gives <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> controllers three or four more seconds to order a shuttle into an emergency landing in case of a sudden failure after liftoff. `` Three to four seconds in a lot of different failure modes is forever,'' says senior <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> controller <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Muratore </PERSON>. From typewriter-style keyboards, controllers can now punch up graphics that trace the shuttle trajectory, duplicate cockpit instrument displays and even mimic the horizon as the astronauts see it from inside their rising space ship. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> is designing artificial intelligence programs to help plug its `` brain drain'' as thousands of experienced Apollo era employees retire. The generic name for such programs is `` expert systems.'' <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> has begun implementing its expert system at the <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> center in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> as part of a multimillion-dollar improvement program scheduled for completion in 1991. <PERSON> Muratore </PERSON> is in charge of developing the system. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> hopes expert systems can capture the knowledge of veteran employees to help younger workers do various jobs. <PERSON> Muratore </PERSON> predicted his system will cut months off the minimum time of two years that controllers must spend in training before being assigned to a flight. `` They have to make a mental picture of what's going on with the shuttle,'' <PERSON> Muratore </PERSON> explained. `` We took some senior controllers and learned how they built their mental models, then programmed the computer to do that for them.'' When shuttles returned to flight in September, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> installed the expert system to help engineers pinpoint trouble in the orbiter's three main engines. It ran in tandem with the traditional system. `` We were prepared to take actions'' based on the new program, <PERSON> Muratore </PERSON> said. `` I do n't know of any other case where somebody has built an expert system and then put life and property on the line that way.'' Since then, <PERSON> Muratore </PERSON> said, the system has become a `` primary tool'' for four controllers who monitor communications, engines, mechanical systems, and guidance and navigation. With the system <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> is phasing out, controllers decipher multiple pages of data displayed on their computer screens, all while monitoring dozens of blinking console lights _ each of which can signal two or more safe or unsafe conditions. In the old system, flight information is stored in two computers and displayed on every controller's console. By comparison, <PERSON> Muratore </PERSON>'s system divides the data among individual consoles, shaving precious seconds off the processing.
