<HEAD>House Panel Wants S&amp;L Owners to Put up More Money</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> members who want savings and loan owners to put up more of their own money when they make loans will be fighting to preserve a legislative victory when they resume work next week on President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s bailout proposal. After hours of debate, the panel voted 36-15 Thursday to require S & amp; L owners by January 1995 to risk $ 3 of `` tangible'' or `` real money'' capital for every $ 100 they lend. Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> praised the action in a statement released after the vote, even though the deadline is 3 -LCB- years later than the June 1991 date sought by the administration. `` Requiring S & amp; Ls to put their own capital at risk ahead of the taxpayers' money is the only way to prevent in the future the unsound business practices that contributed to the current crisis,'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is proposing to spend at least $ 157 billion over 10 years, the bulk of it from taxpayers, to close or merge failed S & amp; Ls. He also wants to restructure the regulatory system, spend $ 50 million a year to investigate and prosecute fraud in S & amp; Ls and boost capital requirements. Assistant Treasury Secretary <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON> said the panel's adoption of a 3 percent layer of protection between S & amp; L loans that could go sour and federal insurance funds was more important than the timetable for achieving it However, consumer groups are worried about a subsequent amendment, sponsored by Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> McCollum </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Fla </LOCATION>., that would permit thrift institutions to continue to risk depositors' funds in subsidiaries involved in high-risk investments such as junk bonds and commercial real estate `` It's a pretty critical loophole,'' said <PERSON> P