represents the value an institution's customer loyalty and name recognition Critics argue that goodwill evaporates when an institution fails and thus provides no protection to government deposit insurance funds. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, about two-thirds of the nation's 3,000 S & amp; Ls can meet the 3 percent tangible standard. Some of those that do not should be able to raise the money, but about 245 may have to seek merger partners, it said. Institutions failing to meet the standard would be subject to growth restrictions and closer regulatory supervision. Rep. <PERSON> Floyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Flake </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, said he intends to offer an amendment Monday that would provide more favorable treatment of goodwill. He and others, including the powerful chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, Rep. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., argue that it is unfair to wipe out the goodwill because during the early 1980s regulators permitted the accounting break to otherwise healthy institutions in exchange for taking over ailing thrifts
