<HEAD>House Panel Sends $1.17 Trillion Budget to Floor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leading lawmakers predict that a $ 1.17 trillion budget for 1990, thrashed out in days of often contentious closed-door meetings by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, will be approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> next week. The panel approved the spending plan on a bipartisan 18-6 vote on Thursday, edging the budget deal completed two weeks ago between President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and congressional leaders closer to enactment. The proposal claims a deficit of $ 99.4 billion, just within the $ 100 billion ceiling required by the Gramm-Rudman balanced budget law. It would hold defense spending below the rate of inflation and give big boosts to education, science and health programs, while cutting agriculture, environment and energy spending. As they finished their work on the document, committee members echoed remarks made frequently in recent days about the direction this year's budget seems to be headed. `` I assume it will pass because there is no alternative,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Olav </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabo </PERSON>, D-Minn., who voted against the proposal in committee Rep. <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, R-Ky., who also opposed the plan, said he believed that the deficit reduction it claimed was largely phony, but that the proposal would be approved anyway `` With the head of steam it's got from the budget summit and from the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> leadership, it will be hard to overcome,'' he said. House Majority Leader <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, D-Wash., who is on the committee, also predicted the measure would clear the chamber, saying he expected little trouble from conservatives over the defense expenditures it permits `` Do you think people will look at the defense money in this bill, with its being blessed by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON>, and say it's not enough?'' <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> has said he believes the cuts in the defense budget will be difficult but are manageable. Because the budget pact between <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and congressional leaders set overall spending limits for defense, domestic programs and foreign aid, those figures are identical in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> versions of the budget. The main differences between the two chambers is in how they distribute domestic funds. Energy programs would get $ 3.8 billion in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> plan and $ 4.2 billion in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Health spending would reach $ 56.2 billion under the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> proposal and $ 55.7 billion under the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Education would get $ 39.1 billion under the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> budget and $ 38.7 billion under the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> budget writers set aside enough money to pay for a Democratic initiative on children, with $ 1.8 billion for child care and more money for Head Start; an increase to $ 1.9 billion for AIDS research and treatment; full-inflation increases in programs for the poor; and a 3.6 percent cost-of-living raise for military and civilian federal workers. Before holding a brief public meeting at which they approved the spending plan, the budget committee met behind closed doors this week, arguing over spending priorities and working out a bipartisan deal. According to meeting participants who asked to not be identified, those sessions resulted in money being transferred to space and science programs, and to veterans programs, from other domestic initiatives. There were also attempts by liberals to slash the defense budget and distribute the money to domestic programs, such as Medicare, AIDS research, low-income programs, veterans health, and anti-drug efforts. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> passed its version of the budget on April 19. That chamber also expects to complete work next week on its spending blueprint.
