<FIRST>r w PM-ReceivingBenefits     04-28 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Receiving Benefits,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>More than One Woman in Five Gets Poverty Benefits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> women are more likely to need anti-poverty assistance than men, as they struggle to raise children on their own and cope with leaner times in old age, a <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> report shows. More than one woman in five _ 20.5 percent _ received help from some major benefits program during a 32-month study reported on by the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday. During the same period the public assistance programs aided 15.8 percent of men in the nation, somewhat less than one out of six. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> McNeil </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Household </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION> said that the difference in need is largely the result of women raising children without a husband present and the preponderance of women in the older age groups. When marriages break up women more often obtain custody of the children, and those families more often lapse into poverty, <PERSON> McNeil </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. In addition, a growing number of single women are raising families of their own, he noted. As of 1987, the bureau said, 34.3 percent of families with a female householder fell below the poverty level. By comparison, 12.5 percent of families with a male householder and no wife, and only 6.0 percent of married couples fell below the poverty level. The analysis showed that more than two-thirds of people living in a female-headed household with no husband present throughout the study period received anti-poverty benefits _ 67.1 percent. The study found that 18.3 percent of all Americans received benefits from at least one of six programs studied. Included were general assistance, Aid to Families with Dependent Children, <ORGANIZATION> Supplemental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Income </ORGANIZATION>, Medicaid, federal food stamps and federal and state rent assistance. Benefits were more likely to go to minorities, to the very young and to people who had not finished high school, according to the report which covered the period from late 1983 to early 1986. `` One of the more important findings was that the likelihood of receiving benefits was very closely tied to the number of months in which income fell below the poverty level,'' <PERSON> McNeil </PERSON> said. `` So, in that sense, the programs appear to be providing benefits to those who need them the most.'' This was the first long-term look at recipients of benefits done by the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>, and thus no past rates were available for comparison, <PERSON> McNeil </PERSON> said. The study will be repeated in the future, he said. Nearly half of black Americans obtained help from one or more programs during the period, at 48.5 percent, the study said. By comparison, the rate was 34.2 percent for Hispanics and 13.9 percent for white Americans. Blacks also were longer-term recipients of help, averaging 11.2 months of benefits during the study period. Hispanics averaged 7.4 months of benefits while it was 2.6 months for white recipients. Overall, women recipients averaged 4.4 months of benefits, compared with 3.0 months for men. By age, people under age 18 were the leading group receiving benefits at 26.6 percent _ and the subgroup under age 6 managed a 30.1 percent rate. Programs benefited 19.9 percent of people aged 18 to 24, while in the 25 to 44 group the rate was 14.7 percent. For people aged 65 and over the rate was 17.9. Benefits were most needed by inner-city residents, at 23.7 percent. The rate was 20.5 percent in rural areas and fell to only 12.3 percent in the suburbs. By region, 20.7 percent of southerners received benefits, followed by 18.0 percent in the West, 16.8 percent in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> and 16.7 percent in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. The study was based on repeated interviews with 19,900 households across the country.
</TEXT>
