<HEAD>Detroit Teamsters Official with two Convictions Named International
VP</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Detroit-area Teamsters official with two convictions for union-related offenses has been named an international vice president of the nation's largest union, raising questions about its pledge to improve its image. The selection of <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Vitale </PERSON> by <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>, though not announced by the union, was confirmed Thursday by <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> sources. A Teamsters spokesman did not return telephone calls seeking comment. The selection comes in the wake of the settlement of a racketeering suit against the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> and a pledge by its leaders to back election reforms and refurbish the union's image. `` <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> surely could have done better than to go out and appoint a guy who has been convicted of taking payoffs both from employers and stealing the union members' money,'' said <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Paff </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> for a <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, a dissident union group based in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Vitale </PERSON>, president of Teamsters Local 283 in <LOCATION> Wyandotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, was convicted twice in the early 1970s, for accepting an illegal payment from a <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> employer and for illegal use of union funds in a plan to buy his wife a car. He received fines and probation for both convictions but was allowed to keep his union job. The prosecutor who handled the racketeering case raised the possibility that a court-appointed administrator agreed to as part of the settlement could review the <PERSON> Vitale </PERSON> appointment. `` The court-appointed administrator will have the authority to review the appointment and to discipline any Teamster officials,'' said assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Mastro </PERSON>. `` There is no statute of limitations on the right to discipline.'' The appointment of an administrator is expected to be made in the next two weeks. That is one of three court-appointed monitoring positions agreed to as part of the settlement of the racketeering suit, which alleged widespread organized crime influence on the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>. Critics within the union characterized the <PERSON> Vitale </PERSON> appointment as a slap at former Teamsters Vice President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> resigned in January in return for being dropped as a defendant in the suit. <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> opposed <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>'s election to succeed the late <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Presser </PERSON> as <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> president. <PERSON> Vitale </PERSON> reportedly had a falling out with <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> in recent years. <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> under Teamsters bylaws can fill vacancies on the union's <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Executive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> _ which consists of the president, secretary-treasurer and 16 international vice presidents _ subject to board approval. He has a solid majority on the board because of recent turnover and has two vacancies still to fill.
</TEXT>
