<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: No Polemics, No Bold Initiatives So far</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After only 100 days, it's hard to tell if President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s foreign policy is intentionally uninspiring or if he is simply taking his time coming to conclusions about <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s role in the world He has pulled back from the polemics of his predecessor, <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, and in a few as yet inconclusive ways, such as a toughening stand toward <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, indicated that he just might adopt a foreign policy that is substantively different from the one he inherited. On the other hand, these changes are so slight it could turn out that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has no bold initiatives in mind, and that like President <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> in the mid-1970s he intends mostly to mark time in the foreign field. An overseas crisis could intervene, forcing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to improvise a response that could lead to a dramatic shift in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy. The rise to power in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in 1985 of <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, for instance, impelled <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to drop his denunciations of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> as an evil empire. The result was a series of negotiations that produced a lessening of tensions and the banning of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet intermediate-range nuclear missiles. So far, international events have not conspired to draw <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> into major decisions. A political scandal in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and growing West German distaste for nuclear weapons could produce severe strains, but <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has given no sign of a shift in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support for <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> determination to modernize <PERSON> Lance </PERSON> missiles in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has worked out a temporary deal with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to supply the Nicaraguan rebels with $ 49.8 million in non-military aid and he has endorsed an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> proposal for elections among Palestinian Arabs to implement self-rule on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>. Both are stopgap measures. They beg the question whether <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will pursue the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> policy of trying to topple the Marxist government in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> or is willing to live with it, and whether he will try to force <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Arabs </LOCATION> into a lasting agreement. The Contra aid package, the product of a March 24 agreement between the administration and the Democratic-led <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, is good only until the Fall. <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> could make enough political concessions by then to get Uncle <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> off its back _ and spare <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> a difficult decision. Less likely is that <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s election plan will induce the Palestinians and their supporters to adopt a gradual and peaceful approach to settling the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> problem <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has already declared himself opposed to Israeli `` occupation'' of sovereignty over the territories. This could be a sign that he intends to pressure <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to yield control. But there is no hint of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> peace plan, of shuttle diplomacy by Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, or that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will summon <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> leaders to Camp <PERSON> David </PERSON>, as President <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> did in 1978 to help squeeze out the peace treaty between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> a year later. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> evidently are committed to the proposition that direct negotiations between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> offer the best hope for an agreement that would hold up. High-profile <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomacy is not part of the picture at this point. In the important sphere of U.S.-Soviet relations, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s troop and missile reduction initiatives are receiving a skeptical response But <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact opened negotiations in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> in March to trim tank and artillery units, and <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> probably will set a date for the resumption of U.S.-Soviet talks on long-range nuclear weapons when he goes to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> May 11. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has the implicit support of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administration as he consolidates his powers. This week, for instance, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> described his purge of 74 <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> voting members and the promotion of several proteges as dramatic. It expressed hope that `` whatever changes occur, their effect is to strengthen and promote the reform process in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> toward greater democratization and openness.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, meanwhile, is encouraging reform in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> with a series of moves that could ease the Soviet ally's $ 39 billion foreign debt. ` ` Liberty is an idea whose time has come in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' he said in a speech last week He probably will visit <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> this summer to maintain <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support for change.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
