<HEAD>Abandoned Babies Filling Hospitals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Many babies born to mothers who use drugs are becoming `` boarders'' who strain staffs and facilities in urban hospitals after being abandoned by their parents, a hospital director told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` The problem that my hospital and hospitals in cities around the country are facing daily is caring for those newborn babies abandoned by drug abusing mothers,'' said <PERSON> Haynes </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. Rice on Thursday told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> and Families that the overcrowding caused by these `` boarder babies'' has become so acute one day he was unable to locate an empty bed anywhere between <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> for an acutely ill infant. Boarder babies are children who remain in hospitals after birth even though they are medically ready for discharge, he said. The problem is being exacerbated in the nation's capital by the rising cross-generational family use of crack cocaine, said <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>. `` Now we are seeing 28 - and 35-year-old grandmothers who are themselves substance abusers and who can not readily step in to provide the social support as in the past. An internal study found the average stay for 27 of the 45 babies being boarded at Howard between August and December 1988 was 42.3 days. The average expected hospital stay for a newborn is three days. `` The longest-stay infant had been in the hospital for 245 days at a cost in excess of $ 250,000,'' said <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, noting the Medicaid payment received by the hospital was set at $ 6,100 regardless of the length of stay or extent of services the child received while there. <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> recommended streamlining foster care and adoption procedures to speed the placement of boarder babies into stable homes. This is not a new phenomenon, he said, explaining that 20 years ago `` when I worked in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, the public hospitals there had about 200 babies on a daily basis who had been abandoned at the hospitals by heroin addicted mothers.'' <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavkin </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> doctor, said a recent report by the city comptroller shows the problem has not abated, indicating maternal drug use was the reason for the boarder status of 49 percent of the more than 300 children under age 2 in city hospitals. <PERSON> Chavkin </PERSON> said the lack of drug treatment facilities for women in general and pregnant women specifically also contributes to the problem.
</TEXT>
