<FIRST>r a PM-TankerSpill-Mate     04-28 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill-Mate,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Mystery Man On The Bridge Could Be Star of NTSB Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 He is the mystery man of the nation's worst oil spill, the third mate who was on watch when the <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION> ran aground and dumped more than 10 million gallons of crude in Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> Little has been seen of Gregory Cousins since the March 24 accident, and federal officials do n't expect him to surface until the May 16-19 hearings in <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION> to assess what happened and how to prevent a recurrence. Capt. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON>, who the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> says was the only person aboard authorized to navigate the tanker through the sound, blamed his third mate when the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> radioed his ship an hour after the wreck. `` <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON> here,'' the skipper answered when <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Cmdr. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> McCall </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> asked for a damage report. `` A little problem here with the third mate, but we're working our way off the reef,'' said <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON>, who tried to rock the ship free before shutting down the engines and waiting for help. Cousins had signed on with <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> as a third mate, although he had obtained his second mate's certification Jan. 12. `` That's not unusual,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaminski </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> `` With fewer positions available, people set sail at positions lower than their license.'' A second mate is the navigator and is in charge of maps and charts. The third mate is in charge of maintenance and the inventory of firefighting equipment. They and the chief mate, who's in charge of the cargo, alternate four-hour watches on the bridge <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON> turned the 987-foot tanker and its 42 million gallons of oil destined for <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, over to Cousins sometime after a state pilot with federal pilot authority left the ship at Rocky Point. <LOCATION> Bligh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reef </LOCATION> was seven miles away. `` At that time the master -LRB- <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON> -RRB- was in the wheelhouse,'' said Coast Guard Cmdr. <PERSON> Darryle </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldron </PERSON>. `` The master had federal pilotage -LRB- authority -RRB- for Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> through the entrance. The mates did n't have the necessary endorsements on their licenses.'' The pilots used to navigate ships out of the sound to the Gulf of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> until the 1980s when a smaller ship taking a pilot back to <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON> capsized in rough seas. The pilot nearly died, and the rules were eased. Cousins, reportedly a resident of <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, was licensed out of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> and obtained his third mate's license March 19, 1986. Coast Guard records in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, showed he had no record of disciplinary action. Cousins is still employed by <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>, said spokesman <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>, but the oil company refused to say where he is working or living. <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON> was dismissed after he tested at .06 on a blood-alcohol test nine hours after the wreck. The legal limit on blood-alcohol tests for ship captains is .04. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said he doubted <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON> would attend the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION>'s hearing in <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION>. `` If a witness is simply going to sit on the stand and take the Fifth -LRB- Amendment right against self-incrimination -RRB- all day ... We'd rather have people give us information That looks like the case with <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON> faces three misdemeanor charges stemming from the accident, including operating a vessel while under the influence. Cousins was a more likely participant in the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> hearing, said <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON>. Other <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> officials confirmed the agency has talked with Cousins and hopes to have a longer interview before the May hearing.
