<FIRST>r a PM-Tattoos     04-28 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tattoos,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Laser Erases Tattoos Without Scars or Pain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new laser technique erases tattoos but spares the skin, providing the first way to get rid of battleships, hearts, old lovers' names or other such decorations without causing scars, researchers say. The treatment uses an intense beam of light called a ruby laser to blast away the colors beneath the skin. `` I think this is the first truly non-scarring therapy for tattoos,'' said Dr. <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rox </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. Dr. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, a member of <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>'s research team, planned to present the results of the laser treatment today at a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dermatology </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Doctors said the laser is almost painless, too. It produces a sensation something like a loosely snapped rubber band. Lasers are already widely used for removing tattoos, but current models burn them off, leaving permanent scars. The new technique also produces high heat, but its effects are much more selective. It uses brief, 100 million-watt flashes of red light, which is absorbed by the tattoo pigment. The heat shatters the bits of pigment imbedded in the skin as well as the cells that hold them. But it does not harm blood vessels or ordinary cells. `` There is clearly a difference between this and other therapies that are used,'' <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said the procedure could become the standard treatment for removing tattoos after it is approved by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, perhaps within two years. Dr. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Arndt </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Beth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> agreed. `` When the ruby laser works well, which looks to be a good deal of the time, the skin remains normal,'' he said. `` That's extraordinary, and it's bringing fancy technology to the level where it can be useful for patient care. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said that in testing so far on 13 people, the laser completely erased about half of the tattoos and faded the rest. However, he said the initial study was intended to find the proper intensity of laser light, and some patients received relatively low doses. Results may be better when higher levels are used routinely. Of 41 tatoos treated, only one small patch of skin measuring less than a square inch became scarred. The laser will not remove red pigment because it does not absorb the red light. Amateur tattoos come off more easily than professionally drawn tattoos, which contain more color. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said that after his team began experimenting with the ruby laser, they discovered that a group of doctors in <LOCATION> Glasgow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, had worked on the same approach and published preliminary results in a British journal. Unless burned or removed surgically, tattoos are permanent. The <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> researchers said that most of the people they have treated so far got them while drunk. One woman had her boyfriend's initials tattooed when she was a teen-ager. The next day she regretted it, and always kept the tattoo covered with a bandage. Tattoos are drawn by puncturing the skin, usually with needles, and inserting pigment that remains after the wound heals over. The variety of laser used in the new treatment was once widely tested for medical purposes, but none of them seemed to work and it was abandoned. The ruby laser is used largely for welding.
</TEXT>
