<HEAD>Techno-Bandit Sentenced To 30 Months For Escape Attempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A West German described by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities as `` the world's top techno-bandit'' was sentenced to an additional 2 -LCB- years in prison and fined $ 40,000 for a daring helicopter prison escape attempt. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Stafford </PERSON> sentenced <PERSON> Werner </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruchhausen </PERSON>, 49, to 30-month concurrent sentences Thursday on each of two counts of conspiracy to escape. The term will be tacked onto a 15-year term <PERSON> Bruchhausen </PERSON> received in 1987 for sales of classified technology to Soviet bloc countries. <PERSON> Stafford </PERSON> criticized letters he got on behalf of <LOCATION> Bruchhausen </LOCATION> which were critical of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> judicial system, saying, `` I thought I ought to let you know this system has provided you with a fair trial.'' Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Dobson </PERSON> urged the judge to exceed sentencing guidelines, which called for a maximum prison term of 30 months. He discounted the defense contention that <PERSON> Bruchhausen </PERSON> was entrapped. `` He was the person who initiated the plan,'' said <PERSON> Dobson </PERSON>. Defense attorney <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Culpepper </PERSON>, who asked the judge to stay within the guidelines, said no decision had been made on an appeal. Authorities foiled <PERSON> Bruchhausen </PERSON>'s escape by setting up a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Customs helicopter as the escape aircraft. He had reportedly offered to pay up to $ 250,000 for assistance. <PERSON> Bruchhausen </PERSON> was taken into custody by an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent and four prison officers as he started toward the aircraft that had swooped down over the softball field in the prison recreation yard last August. He was later transferred to the federal penitentiary in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. The West German citizen began serving his sentence at the <LOCATION> Tallahassee </LOCATION> prison in May 1987. <PERSON> Bruchhausen </PERSON> and three others were indicted in August 1981 in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> on charges of conspiracy and violating the Export Administration Act, the Arms Export and Control Act and federal income tax laws. The 60-count indictment charged that from January 1977 through June 5, 1980, <PERSON> Bruchhausen </PERSON> and the others `` conspired to export from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> various high technology commodities'' to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and elsewhere without export licenses from the State and Commerce departments. At that time, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Customs Commissioner <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabb </PERSON> called <PERSON> Bruchhausen </PERSON> `` one of the world's top techno-bandits.'' He was arrested on May 8, 1985, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, extradited the following year and convicted of wire fraud in 1987. <PERSON> Bruchhausen </PERSON> allegedly smuggled a microwave receiver system, semiconductor manufacturing equipment, a computer system and other military and scientific items to the Soviet bloc through dummy corporations in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>.
