 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> held a meeting last week to discuss how to handle a transfer of presidential power if <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> were incapacitated, White House press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> says. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> called the unannounced session April 18 `` just a routine meeting, just a process meeting, how the process would work.'' The 25th Amendment to the Constitution prescribes circumstances under which the vice president would assume power from the president, and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> temporarily took over from former President <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> when he had colon cancer surgery on July 13, 1985. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said Thursday that `` precise guidelines'' were adopted during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration for implementing the Amendment. `` I do n't know that there's anything -LRB- more -RRB- to decide,'' he said. `` It's all very routine. The processes were worked out in the last administration.'' He said he did not recall that that process had ever been made public. On the other hand, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said he recalled talking about the process when <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was undergoing periodic cancer checkups. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, who was traveling in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, said of the report today, `` I have absolutely no comment on that. I have no comment.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, quoting an anonymous <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> source, reported today that the meeting was kept secret because of sensitivity to previous Democratic charges that <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> lacked experience to handle the job of president. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said he did not know who participated in the meeting but said it was a private sessi