<SECOND>PM-Earthquake,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moderate Quake Felt In Six States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Dishes rattled and houses shook, but no damages or injuries were reported from an earthquake centered in <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and felt in five other states, authorities said. The earthquake hit at 11:48 a.m. CDT Thursday and measured 4.7 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale of ground motion. It was centered in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, 10 miles north of <LOCATION> Blytheville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark </LOCATION>. The temblor _ in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> _ was the strongest in the region since 1976, said <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Jorgenson </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Survey </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Earthquake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Golden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Earthquake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Southeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Missouri </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Girardeau </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, said the quake also was felt in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hester </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Mayfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, about 20 miles north of the <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> border, was perched on her roof, painting, when the earthquake hit. The quake lasted about 15 seconds. `` There was a loud boom, and about that time everything went to shaking. ... I do n't know which was shaking worse _ me or the house,'' Ms. <PERSON> Hester </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Pemiscot </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff's Deputy <PERSON> Rodney </PERSON> <PERSON> Ivie </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> said his office had received many calls, but none reporting damage or injuries. `` They were worried because they were n't sure what it was,'' <PERSON> Ivie </PERSON> said. `` They had a pretty good idea, you know, but they wanted to make sure.'' The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Madrid </ORGANIZATION> seismic zone was the center of a series of great earthquakes that rocked the area during the winter of 1811-12. Officials have warned repeatedly that a serious earthquake can be expected during the next several years in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> seismic area, which stretches roughly from southern <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>. Thursday's was the strongest quake in the region since March 25, 1976, when one registered 4.9, said <PERSON> Jorgenson </PERSON>. The <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase in magnitude. So a reading of 7.5 means an earthquake 10 times stronger than one of 6.5. An earthquake of 3.5 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale can cause slight damage, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6 severe damage. A 7 reading is a major earthquake, capable of widespread heavy damage; 8 is a `` great'' quake, capable of tremendous damage. The <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale was unavailable in 1811-1812, but those quakes have been estimated at 8.2 to 8.3 on the scale. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Madrid </ORGANIZATION> quakes affected much of the eastern <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, felt as far away as <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, but the immediate area then was sparsely settled and there was relatively little local damage.
