<HEAD>Investigator: Dispatcher's Mistake Caused Derailment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A mistake by a <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> dispatcher with 23 years experience caused the April 6 derailment of <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION>'s Silver Star near <LOCATION> Emporia </LOCATION>, a federal investigator said. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Inglis </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that the dispatcher, based at <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION>'s new central dispatch center in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, had radioed the engineer that the Silver Star would be switching tracks in <LOCATION> Emporia </LOCATION> _ four miles beyond the point where the switch had been set. <LOCATION> Emporia </LOCATION> is about 50 miles south of <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>. The engineer failed to slow for the switch because he did n't expect it so soon, <PERSON> Inglis </PERSON> said The train plowed into the switch at its normal cruising speed of 59 mph instead of the recommended crossover speed of 15 mph. Both engines and the first eight cars of the 18-car train jumped the track, causing minor injuries to 34 of the train's 519 passengers and $ 1.8 million in damage. <PERSON> Inglis </PERSON> said tests found no evidence of drug or alcohol use by anyone involved in the train's routing or operation. He said the dispatcher had a perfect work record before the derailment. The man is still at his post and likely will keep his job, the investigator said. The safety board's final report on the accident, due in June, probably will recommend changes in operating procedures at the dispatch center, <PERSON> Inglis </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> has about 19,000 miles of track in 20 states plus <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>.
