<HEAD>City Plans Big Party For 200th Anniversary Of Washington's Inauguration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Red, white and blue will be the rage this weekend as the 200th anniversary of <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>'s inauguration is celebrated with a flotilla of ships, a fireworks display and a parade led by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s swearing-in as the first president was watched by some 20,000, just 10,000 fewer than the city's population in 1789. More than 2 million are expected to gather to watch the bicentennial events. The highlight will be the inaugural commemoration at Federal Hall on Sunday, marking the moment when <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> put his hand to the Bible and swore to `` faithfully execute the office of president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will speak at the ceremony _ which falls on his 101st day in office. And a white-haired Philadelphian, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sommerfield </PERSON>, will play the part of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and deliver part of the first president's inaugural address. The city kicks off the festivities Saturday with a flotilla in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>. Thirteen <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> ships representing the original states will be joined by 50 commercial and civilian vessels coming down the <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. At night, a fireworks spectacular called `` Hail to the Chief,'' narrated by <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Cronkite </PERSON>, will emblazon the sky. Scenes of pyrotechnics will tell the history of the presidency. Prior to Sunday's commemoration, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and other dignitaries will attend an ecumenical service at <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION><LOCATION> 's </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chapel </LO