<HEAD>Two Limpet Mines Explode In Johannesburg, No One Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two limpet mines exploded in trash cans in downtown <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> early today, shattering store windows but causing no injuries, police said. The first explosion shortly after noon blew up a trash bin at the entrance of a local department store. It occurred across from a building housing several <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and British news organizations, including <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> CBS-TV </ORGANIZATION>, The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION>. The second explosion occurred two hours later in front of a furnishing store seven blocks away. Bombings had dropped off sharply since a protest campaign last October against the racially separate nationwide municipal elections. While there had been no bombs in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> in months, several were reported in the <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> area and in the Xhosa tribal homelands of <LOCATION> Ciskei </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Transkei </LOCATION>. Sixteen people have been injured by about 20 bombs this year. Police named no suspect for today's bombings, although they usually blame the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the largest guerrilla organization waging a sabotage campaign to end apartheid and rule by a white-dominated government. The <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> seldom comments on individual bombings, but they sometimes occur after an event considered significant to the organization. Three <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas were sentenced to death Thursday, and a fourth received a 25-year prison sentence in connection with four killings and two bombings that injured 17 people in 1986. The trial was in <LOCATION> Delmas </LOCATION>, a farm town northeast of <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>.
