<HEAD>Strong Quake Jolts Greece, No Damage Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VOLOS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A strong earthquake jolted central <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> today but no damage or injuries were reported. The <ORGANIZATION> Athens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seismological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said the quake, which occurred at 7:02 a.m., measured 5.0 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale and was centered in the <LOCATION> Aegean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, about 85 miles north of the capital. `` We felt the quake but we had no reports of damage or injuries,'' said a police officer in the central Greek port of <LOCATION> Volos </LOCATION>. The officer, who spoke on condition of anonymity in accordance with <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> practice, said, `` We have many Easter visitors here and at the nearby islands and fortunately there was no panic.'' More than 1 million Athenians have left the capital to spend the weekend of the Greek Orthodox Easter in the countryside, police said. A quake measuring 5.0 can cause considerable damage if its epicenter is in a populated area. The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a seismograph. Every increase of one number means the ground motion is 10 times greater.
