<HEAD>Bounty Mutiny Re-enacted In South Seas On 200th Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of history's most notorious naval revolts, the mutiny on the <LOCATION> Bounty </LOCATION>, was re-enacted today in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seas </LOCATION> by descendants of Capt. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bligh </PERSON> and his rebellious first officer, <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> <PERSON> Christian </PERSON>. `` It was a wonderful moment, the ghosts of <PERSON> Bligh </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> were with us today,'' said Capt. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Bligh-Ware </PERSON>, whose great-great-great-grandfather was set adrift off the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> island nation of <LOCATION> Tonga </LOCATION> on April 28, 1789. `` Today was probably the most jovial mutiny in history,'' the 62-year-old <PERSON> Bligh-Ware </PERSON> added. `` We popped champagne corks and it was fun.'' <PERSON> Bligh-Ware </PERSON>'s had only to circumnavigate his ship _ a replica of the Bounty built from British admiralty charts _ in a long boat. His famous ancestor, forced from his ship, was joined by 18 loyal crewmen who sailed a 23-foot open boat about 4,200 miles in 47 days to <LOCATION> Timor </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, in what is still regarded as a remarkable feat. Christian sailed the Bounty back to <LOCATION> Tahiti </LOCATION> and then spent months searching the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> for a haven, knowing he would be hanged if caught. The mutineers eventually settled on <LOCATION> Pitcairn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, one of the world's most remote settlements. There they burned the ship. Their descendants moved to <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, off the east coast of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, in the 1850s. Some later returned to <LOCATION> Pitcairn </LOCATION> and the populations of both islands to this day are predominantly of mutineer ancestry. <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosebery </PERSON>, owner of the replica <PERSON> Bounty </PERSON>, organized the re-enactment about 2,100 miles east of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. He said that six of the 36 passengers and crew were direct descendants of the mutineers. The passengers paid an average of $ 4,800 for the month-long voyage from <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Tahiti </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tonga </LOCATION>. They adopted the names of mutineers for the re-enactment. The replica ship, built in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> in 1979, was used in the 1984 movie `` The Bounty,'' starring Australian actor <PERSON> Mel </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>. `` Bligh-Ware, like his father and grandfather, is a qualified captain in the Australian merchant navy,'' said <PERSON> Rosebery </PERSON>. `` He also bears a remarkable resemblance to the 18th century <PERSON> Bligh </PERSON> while <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> <PERSON> Christian </PERSON>'s great-great-great-grandson, <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Christian </PERSON>, has the rank of lieutenant commander in the Australian <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. The sea seems to run in their families' blood.'' Commemorative stamps that went on sale today in <LOCATION> Tonga </LOCATION> depict <PERSON> Bligh </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Bounty </LOCATION>, a navigational compass he used and the small boat on which <PERSON> Bligh </PERSON> and his men were abandoned. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Bligh </PERSON> died, the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> navy captain's reputation is being reassessed Long regarded as the villain of the mutiny, he now has almost heroic stature. `` The old view of <PERSON> Bligh </PERSON> as a bully is largely legend and I'm afraid that <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Laughton </PERSON>, <PERSON> Trevor </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> Gable </PERSON> and <PERSON> Marlon </PERSON> <PERSON> Brando </PERSON> have a lot to do with it,'' said <PERSON> Baron </PERSON> <PERSON> Terence </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON>, a retired <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> admiral The 68-year-old admiral spoke to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at the opening of an exhibition marking the 200th anniversary of the mutiny.
