<HEAD>Poll Gives President Bush A `C' Grade For First 100 Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If the White House can be compared to a schoolhouse, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> earned a `` C'' during his first 100 days, according to a poll published today. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s predecessor, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, got a `` B'' in a similar poll the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> conducted after his first 100 days in office. However, the newspaper noted <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s popularity was bolstered by an assassination attempt 70 days after he entered the Oval Office. The poll also found that 47 percent of those interviewed `` approve of the way <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is handling his job as president.'' Eighteen percent said they disapprove, and 35 percent said they have no opinion. The newspaper said that at the same juncture in <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s presidency, 80 percent of those surveyed approved of the former president's job performance When people were asked, `` What kind of a grade would you give President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>?'' the result was a `` C'' average. The survey, conducted by Times pollster I.A. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, interviewed a random sample of 2,160 people nationwide for four days, ending last Tuesday. The newspaper said the margin of error was 3 percentage points in either direction. Sixty-seven percent of those polled have a positive impression of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, 20 percent unfavorable and 13 percent unsure. One hundred days into <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s first term in 1981, 83 percent of those surveyed said they had an overall positive impression of him. The poll found that 52 percent of those surveyed disapproved of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s handling of the Alaskan oil spill, 25 percent voiced approval and the remainder were unsure. On other issues, 34 percent approved of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s steps to control semiautomatic weapons, and 26 percent disapproved; 24 percent approved of his handling of the savings and loan crisis, and 27 percent disapproved. The total added up to more than 100 percent because of multiple responses.
