<HEAD>Chinese Renew Pledge To Halt Aid To Rebels In Cambodia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A senior <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> official has renewed pledges to halt military aid to guerrillas in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> after the total pullout of Vietnamese troops, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s foreign minister said today. Meanwhile, exiled <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> resistance leader Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> today rejected proposals for general elections following the Sept. 30 withdrawal of the estimated 50,000-70 ,000 Vietnamese troops from his country as `` illegal and absolutely unacceptable. <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>, in a written statement, said <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>'s plan to have all troops leave <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> by the end of September was a `` farce,'' because the Vietnamese-backed government of Premier <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> remains in power. Vietnamese forces invaded <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in late 1978, ousting the pro-Chinese <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> regime that massacred hundreds of thousands of Cambodians. <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>, toppled from power in a 1970 coup, now heads a coalition of three resistance groups that includes the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON>'s government has reportedly said it will hold general elections within three months after the Vietnamese withdrawal. <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>, who will meet <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION> May 2-3, discounted the validity of any the elections. <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON>'s government is `` nothing but a creation and creature of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'' that `` has no right to to organize ` general elections,''' he said <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> has said the Vietnamese withdrawal from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> should be supervised by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and that <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON>'s government should be dissolved prior to a general election, demands the Cambodian premier has rejected. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Nguyen </PERSON> <PERSON> Co </PERSON> <PERSON> Thach </PERSON> said a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> vice foreign minister made the pledge to halt military aid when he received a copy of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s April 5 declaration of a total withdrawal. <PERSON> Thach </PERSON> did not name the vice minister. `` They say they will stop once the Vietnamese are all withdrawn, then they will stop their military aid,'' <PERSON> Thach </PERSON> said, adding he was confident the pledge would be kept. <PERSON> Thach </PERSON> also said <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Dinh </PERSON> <PERSON> Nho </PERSON> <PERSON> Liem </PERSON> will go to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> for a second round of talks to try to resolve differences over <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. The talks are to be held May 8-10. The first round, held in January, was the first high-level meeting between the two countries in more than nine years. Sino-Vietnamese relations have been strained since the 1970s over border conflicts, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s ties with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, and the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> conflict. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is the main supplier of arms to a guerrilla coalition fighting Vietnamese troops that invaded <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in late 1978. Thach spoke with reporters while attending a symposium in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> on turning <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> into a peaceful trading zone once the conflict over <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> is resolved.
