<HEAD>Residents Don't Buy Exxon's Perception Of Cleanup Progress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Tanker Spill-Mate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hours after <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> showed off its beach-cleaning effort to reporters, an oil company executive got an earful when he tried to convince a fishing community that things were looking better. Exxon got good reviews from a state geologist who watched <LOCATION> Smith </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> being prepared for pregnant seals. But citizens of <PERSON> Cordova </PERSON> let <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> vice president <PERSON> Luyesse </PERSON> <PERSON> LeGrange </PERSON> know they do n't see the same progress. <PERSON> Michele </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Leary </PERSON>, one of 300 people at <ORGANIZATION> Cordova </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>'s gym Thursday night to talk with <PERSON> LeGrange </PERSON> and others coordinating the spill cleanup, disputed <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s claims about the number of skimmers it operates. When <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> said 19 were working in the sound, an overflight by pilots for the <ORGANIZATION> Cordova </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fishermen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> found only three, she said. Another occasion <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> said it had 45 skimmers at work and the union found only five. `` When can we expect to see the situation improve?'' asked <PERSON> O'Leary </PERSON>, a member of the fishermen's union. `` I hardly think that's the case with all the equipment we have out there,'' <PERSON> LeGrange </PERSON> said. `` I'd be most suprised if we have equipment not working.'' After a slow start with officials questioning each other, the two-hour meeting began to get lively as the audience was allowed to join the inquiry. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelso </PERSON>, the state's chief environmentalist, said, `` There has been a long pattern of claims by <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> that do n't bear out when people go look at what's happening.'' <PERSON> Kelso </PERSON> said he was n't accusing LeGrange of lying, but that `` nobody believes'' the company's recent announcement that the shoreline cleanup was ahead of schedule _ a mention that drew laughs from the audience. `` I can tell you this is not a technical issue, not a biological issue or an economic issue,'' <PERSON> Kelso </PERSON> continued. `` It's a moral issue. Until Exxon steps up to their moral responsibility and stops trying to shift blame to somebody else we're going to have problems getting the kind of performance we all expect, whether it's in the water or on the shore.'' <PERSON> LeGrange </PERSON> denied there was any shifting of blame. `` But perhaps there's some sharing that needs to be considered,'' he said. `` In the end, the truth will come out in hearings, in court rooms where people are testifying under oath and subject to cross examination.'' <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> hearings on the accident and the emergency response have been set for May 16-19 in <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION>. The tone of the town meeting was sharp but polite, a contrast to the first meeting of <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> officials and <PERSON> Cordova </PERSON> residents dependent on fishing in <LOCATION> Prince </LOCATION> <LOCATION> William </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sound </LOCATION> for their livelihood. At the earlier meeting, speakers were interrupted and there was considerable shouting. The confrontation occurred shortly after the Exxon Valdez wrecked on <LOCATION> Bligh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reef </LOCATION> and put more than 10 millions of oil into the sound. The newly arrived USS Juneau sent its first crews to beaches on <LOCATION> Smith </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> Thursday, with reporters on hand to watch water hoses turned on the thick, black goop coating the rocks. Standing on the beach was difficult. A shoreline three football fields long should take about three days to clean, said <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartley </PERSON>, a field manager for the cleanup. But a worker struggling to maintain his footing on the beach's oil-slickened rocks disagreed It takes 10 or 15 minutes of high-pressure spraying to wash the oil off a rubber work suit, said <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> of <PERSON> Cordova </PERSON>, who joined the cleanup crew for nearly $ 17 an hour after his work as a fishermen was imperiled by the spill. `` And they say they're going to have this beach cleaned in three days,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. `` I'd call that extremely optimistic.''
