<HEAD>Workers Take Part in March, Support Students</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At the Xidan intersection near the city's center, workers and unemployed youths broke through a line of about 200 police to help students maintain their pro-democracy march to <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>. `` We're opening a road for them,'' said one worker, carrying one of his shoes, which had fallen off during the scuffle. `` The people outnumber the students now.'' Just west of the central square, hundreds of workers surrounded the final line of security forces. `` Give way to the students!'' they shouted, their voices bouncing off the red-brick walls of the <LOCATION> Forbidden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. As the officers' ranks folded, the crowd broke out cheering. Defying threats that they might lose their jobs, thousands of workers on Thursday took part in the 20-mile student march, swelling the number of participants to 150,000. `` If <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s children have the courage to come out, then its fathers do, too,'' said a middle-aged electrician as he marched with his colleagues. `` We're all taking sick days.'' Scores of workers at the <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Light </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> handed marchers dumplings and drinks. At a construction site nearby, work stopped temporarily and workers waved from atop a 15-story building. Workers packed every corner, sitting atop buildings, billoards and subway entrances. `` Long live students! Struggle till the end!'' they chanted as the crowd moved by. The spontaneous action was an indication of widespread opposition to the government. It also bore testimony to student efforts earlier this week to bring their case to the people. `` The government should not stop people from speaking,'' said an elderly dentist. `` I'm too old to push soldiers, but I can still walk with them.'' `` My factory may fire me but I do n't care,'' said a foreman at a bus plant, as he walked near the head of the protest. `` These kids need help, and I'm here to provide it.'' Student protests began last week following the April 15 death of ousted <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaobang </PERSON>. Workers did not start appearing in the throngs until Saturday, when 150,000 students and their supporters occupied Tiananmen Square during <PERSON> Hu </PERSON>'s funeral, calling for a free press and an end to corruption in the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. But they did not start actively participating until Thursday. Since the Saturday protest, bands of student activists on street corners have given speeches and collected money for their protest. Workers said they agreed with student opposition to corruption, nepotism and special privileges. Many senior officials in state-run factories engage in corruption, making huge profits while their employees live on fixed salaries. `` I read one of their leaflets and it made sense,'' said a young driver. `` I know the party leader in my company is corrupt and the students want a clean government.'' Some workers said they would keep on supporting the students, but it was unclear to what extent. `` Do you know what this is?'' one worker asked. `` It is <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> standing up.''
