<HEAD>Prosecutors Ask For Life Sentence for Hamadi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prosecutors today demanded a life sentence for <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> for his role in the hijacking of a <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> plane and the slaying of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sailor. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, is charged with murder and air piracy in the June 1985 hijacking. He admitted taking part in the hijacking but denies killing <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> diver <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON>. In closing arguments, chief prosecutor <PERSON> Achim </PERSON> <PERSON> Thiel </PERSON> said although it could not be proved <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> pulled the trigger of the gun that killed <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON>, `` it was a clear case, at a minimum, of felony murder.'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Korneck </PERSON>, the assistant prosecutor in the trial, which opened July 5, 1988, said: `` It was an attack against the foundations of civilization.'' `` There was no excuse for what happened. It can not be justified or excused,'' <PERSON> Korneck </PERSON> said, referring to the hijacking, <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON>'s murder and the brutal beatings of passengers `` There was nothing in the evidence presented that would justify a milder sentence,'' <PERSON> Korneck </PERSON> said. Thirty-nine Americans were held hostage 17 days after the jet was commandeered while on a flight from <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>. A verdict is not expected until the second half of May. Life imprisonment is the maximum penalty for murder and air piracy in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Under West German law, an accomplice can be convicted of murder even if he did not pull the trigger. `` It can not be proved that <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> killed <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> with his own hands. But he is at a minimum equally guilty,'' <PERSON> Thiel </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> has bl