<HEAD>Judges Challenge Right Of Historians To Reprint Letters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a little-noticed decision, a federal appeals court challenged the right of historians and biographers to reprint letters, diaries and other unpublished primary source material without permission. The ruling last week upheld on a technicality <ORGANIZATION> Henry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s right to print an unflattering book about <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Hubbard </PERSON>, the founder of the <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scientology </ORGANIZATION> A Danish corporation related to the church maintained that use of a <PERSON> Hubbard </PERSON> letter constituted copyright infringement and sought to bar the book, `` Bare-Faced Messiah'' by <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>. The three-judge panel of the 2nd <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> ruled unanimously April 19 that the plaintiffs had sued too late. The opinion signed by Judges <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. Miner and <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> X. </PERSON> <PERSON> Altimari </PERSON> read: `` The <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> denied an injunction for several reasons, one being the existence of special circumstances in which free speech interests were said to outweigh the interests of the copyright owner. We are not persuaded, however, that any First Amendment concerns not accommodated by the Copyright Act are implicated in that action. `` An author's expression of an idea, as distinguished from the idea itself, is not considered subject to the public's ` right to know.''' <PERSON> Floyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON>, a lawyer who specializes in First Amendment cases, said of the decision, `` What they do is reject totally the notion that the First Amendment has any role to play in deciding whether to issue an injunction in a copyright case.'' In a separate opinion, Chief Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON> sided with the trial judge, <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Laval </PERSON>, who also denied an injunction in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Court in August but said the courts should consider the free-speech rights of an author as well as the copyright interests of the plaintiff, especially if the material quoted is essential to demonstrate the point of a criticism. <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON> said his colleagues' opinion `` tends to cast in concrete'' the language Miner used to decide a similar case involving a biography of author <PERSON> J.D </PERSON>. <PERSON> Salinger </PERSON>. In October 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> let stand the <ORGANIZATION> 2nd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION>'s decision barring <ORGANIZATION> Random </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> from publishing the biography by <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> unless brief quotations from and paraphrases of <PERSON> Salinger </PERSON>'s letters were deleted. The appeals court ruled that the letters, which had been donated to libraries and were open to scholarly perusal, still belonged to the writer.
