<TEXT>
 A woman who was infected with the AIDS virus through a blood transfusion will not get any damages from the blood bank that handled it, a jury has ruled. The jury found Thursday that the <ORGANIZATION> Irwin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Blood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> was not negligent in its method of screening donors before the spring of 1985, when blood banks nationwide began using a test for the HIV infection. <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Dale </PERSON>, 59, underwent heart bypass surgery in February 1984 and received blood from Irwin Memorial. She was found to have AIDS two years later. The verdict was returned following a three-week trial. It was the first case tried against <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> since the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> blood bank suffered the industry's first-ever loss in an AIDS case last December.
