<FIRST>r i PM-WorldAnglicans     04-28 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-World Anglicans,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Leaders Urge Compromise on Women Bishops</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For Release 10 a.m. EDT, Time Set by Source</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A church commission today urged that the world's 70 million Anglicans concentrate on what unites them and avoid further divisions over the issue of women bishops `` Bishops should take every opportunity to emphasize their fundamental agreement on matters of faith,'' it said. The Archbishop of <ORGANIZATION> Canterbury </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON>, assigned the commission to report on how the unity of the 27 self-governing Anglican churches in 164 countries can be preserved in the face of the disagreement. The dispute deepened in February when <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Episcopalians consecrated <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> as the first Anglican female bishop, in their <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> diocese. The 18,000-word document, `` Report of the Archbishop of <ORGANIZATION> Canterbury </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Communion and Women in the Episcopate,'' was published simultaneously in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Larnaca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, where the Anglican primates met to consider that and other issues. Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> said in a letter to <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON> that the insistence of some Anglican churches on having women priests and bishops appeared to block progress toward Catholic-Anglican reconciliation. The <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> retains an all-male priesthood, and it split with the <ORGANIZATION> Anglican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in the 16th century Reformation. <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON>, spiritual head of the Church of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and world Anglican leader, will meet with the pope in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> Sept. 29-Oct. 2, primarily to discuss unity of their churches, a consultation their predecessors began in 1966 The commission's report dismissed suggestions that a diocese divided on women bishops might have two bishops catering to opposing views. `` The bishop is an embodiment and agent of unity and continuity in the church,'' the report said. It stressed that bishops must take care not to become focal points of dissent in dioceses that are split on the issue. The report recommended that in dioceses with strong views for and against women priests and bishops, a compromise first worked out by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Episcopalians should be adopted. The compromise allows any congregation rejecting a woman bishop to petition for a male `` Episcopal visitor'' bishop to administer confirmations. `` Provision for <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> visitors is a way of exercising pastoral care,'' said the unanimous report written by six ordained men and an English woman theologian. It proposed that women bishops ordaining priests should do so collegially with a male bishop to meet the objections of church members who feel they could not recognize the ordinations of a woman. `` That would protect the interests of the person ordained and the communities in which he or she may minister in the future,'' the report said. <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON> set up the commission at the request of the Lambeth Conference of Anglican bishops in August, when they knew that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Episcopalians, who have ordained more than 1,200 women to the priesthood, were preparing to approve the first woman bishop. The conference declared that practical pastoral arrangements would have to be made in all Anglican churches and dioceses for those unable to accept women bishops. The majority of Anglican churches, including the Church of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, still rejects women priests. A number of Anglican bishops have said they might reluctantly accept women priests, but could never accept a woman bishop because it is against belief and tradition. They say it was no accident that <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> chose only men as disciples. Archbishop of Armagh <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Eames </PERSON>, who chaired the commission, said the different views on women bishops were reflected by its members, who met for nine days of talks in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> in November and in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in March. The other commission members were Bishop <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Adetiloye </PERSON>, Primate of All <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>; Archbishop <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carnley </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Perth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>; Bishop <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyer </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, Bishop <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hope </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Wakefield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>; the Rev. Dr. <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theology </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, and Dr. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON>, theological secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION>'s board of mission and unity.
