<HEAD>Governor Says Louisiana's Future Rides On Tax Referendum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The future of a state that masks its poverty with an image of fun, food and crooked politics rides on a Saturday referendum to give <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> the power to change its tax system, Gov. <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>'s plan shifts the tax base, putting more of a load on consumers and giving businesses incentives to move into the state and expand. The plan also includes a $ 1.4 billion program to improve highways, airports and shipping ports. The transportation portion would be funded by a gasoline tax increase of 4 cents a gallon. If the referendum is defeated, the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> would have to cut more than $ 600 million from an already tight budget, which <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said is impossible. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> has touted the plan as a way of creating jobs in a state that has the nation's highest unemployment rate and ending <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s dependence on the petroleum industry. The governor, who took office 13 months ago with a pledge to erase what lawmakers have called the state's banana republic image, wo n't predict victory. `` What frightens me are those who might not look at the plan at all and be persuaded by something else in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> politics _ old wars, old wounds, old alliances, business as usual,'' <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said Thursday. He said he also feared that opponents he did not name might spread `` street money,'' a term for vote buying, but he would n't elaborate Two polls conducted over the past week vary in their results. One poll showed 48 percent of 812 voters questioned backing the plan, with 28 percent opposed and 25 percent undecided, with numbers rounded and a margin of error of plus or minus 3.5 points. A second poll says it's too close to call: Of 750 voters questioned, 40 percent were for the plan, 38 percent against, and 22 percent undecided, with a 3.6-point margin of error. Secretary of State <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> <PERSON> McKeithen </PERSON> said he expects more than 40 percent of the state's 2 million registered voters to cast ballots on the proposed constitutional amendment giving the Legislature the power to change the tax system. The plan, promoted by businesses and other proponents in a $ 1 million blitz of television and radio spots, newspaper ads and mailed circulars, would cost an extra $ 126 million over the current tax load. Opponents, however, point out that as of July 1, the tax load increase is $ 526 million. Last summer, the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> approved a one-year sales tax increase of $ 500 million to avoid government bankruptcy. The increase, in the form of canceling longtime exemptions on purchases of food and utilities, will expire July 1. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>'s package keeps about $ 400 million of that tax on a permanent basis. `` White man speak with forked tongue,'' state Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>. `` He says the plan is -LRB- almost -RRB- tax neutral without the gas tax but if it does n't pass, he says we'll have a $ 600 million deficit. He ca n't have it both ways.'' <PERSON> Duke </PERSON>, a former <PERSON> Ku </PERSON> <PERSON> Klux </PERSON> <PERSON> Klan </PERSON> leader, was elected to the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> in February and became the most vocal of the tax opponents, who have raised about $ 60,000 to fight the plan.
