<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The governing party forced the budget through the lower house of Parliament today over an opposition boycott, opening the way for Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> to step down as promised because of a scandal. It was the first time since World War II that the governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> bucked the Japanese tradition of consensus and used its majority to pass a budget despite a boycott. Chairwoman <PERSON> Takako </PERSON> <PERSON> Doi </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the largest opposition group, said the move was `` an outrage ... and a serious challenge to the people.'' She demanded the government resign and let the opposition govern. `` We are determined to continue to fight until we win the dissolution of the Diet -LRB- parliament -RRB- and get new elections called,'' she said. The deputy speaker of the lower house, <PERSON> Shinnen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatagaya </PERSON>, said he would resign to protest the handling of the budget. An independent lawmaker, <PERSON> Yukio </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoshima </PERSON>, told reporters he was quitting the upper house in a similar protest. Ms. <PERSON> Doi </PERSON> and the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Eiichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagasue </PERSON>, said the government was trying to cover up the influence-peddling scandal. Nagasue accused the government of an `` unjustifiable debasement of parliamentary democracy.'' Opposition politicians blocked the hall outside the house chamber in an attempt to halt the vote, but guards pushed them aside to get Speaker <PERSON> Kenzaburo </PERSON> <PERSON> Hara </PERSON> into the 512-seat chamber. After the 281-1 vote _ one independent cast a `` no'' ballot _ <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> bowed to the chamber, which was nearly a third empty. He promised on Tuesday that we would resign after the budget has been enacted. `` To be honest, I am feeling relief, but the budget still has to go through the upper house and I hope it will be passed quickly,'' he told reporters later. Asked if he intends to stay in office until the passage, <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> said, `` You can take it that way.'' Under the constitution, the $ 455 billion budget automatically takes effect May 27 if the less powerful upper house does not act on it. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> said he would step down to take responsibility for a bribery and stock-profiteering scandal that has deeply shaken the public's trust in government. The scandal involving <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, an information and publishing conglomerate, has dominated Japanese politics since it surfaced in June. Prosecutors say Recruit sold unlisted stocks at bargain prices to about 160 political and business figures. The buyers profited handsomely when the stock went public, authorities say. The only remaining hurdle to <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s resignation is selection of a successor. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> planned a weeklong visit to Southeast Asian countries beginning Saturday, and observers believe he will leave office shortly afterward. The apparent top choice of party leaders, former Foreign Minister <PERSON> Masayoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Ito </PERSON>, 75, has refused suggestions he take the job. He said again today the job is too heavy a burden for him because of his age and poor health. <PERSON> Ito </PERSON> is known as `` Mr. Clean'' because of his humble political style. He suffers from diabetes, and government officials say his doctor has recommended he work no more than three hours a day. Earlier today, <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> attended the funeral of <PERSON> Ihei </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoki </PERSON>, his top aide and fund controller, who committed suicide Wednesday. <PERSON> Aoki </PERSON> resigned last year after it was disclosed he had purchased bargain-priced stock from Recruit. This week, <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> admitted Recruit loaned $ 384,000 to his campaign in <PERSON> Aoki </PERSON>'s name.
