<HEAD>TWA Jumbo Jet Lost Part of Wing Slat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 flying from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> with more than 200 people on board lost part of a wing slat as it prepared to land at <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, the airline said today. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> said officers from the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accident </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> have launched an inquiry into the April 20 incident, which a <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman called a `` minor accident.'' Aviation experts said the loss of a slat may affect low speed handling and might mean an aircraft having to land at a faster speed. The leading edge slats are six feet long and positioned along the front of each wing to increase lift. They are operated hydraulically to change the air flow over the wing and allow the aircraft to land at a slower speed. A <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, who demanded anonymity, said a two-foot piece of the slat between the fuselage and the No. 3 engine on the right wing fell off after a bolt sheared. The shearing forced up the flap, breaking off a section of it, the spokesman said. However, he said the damage did not cause any problems with the handling of the aircraft and denied there had been any emergency. `` It did not affect the aerodynamics of the aircraft and the plane made a perfectly safe landing. The pilot would probably not have been aware that anything was wrong until he had landed ... it was a perfectly routine landing,'' he said. The spokesman said the piece that fell off would have weighed about four pounds. He said authorities were notified when the piece was discovered missing. It has not been found, he said. `` It is impossible to say exactly where it was lost because the crew felt no bump or anything like that. It would have been when the aircraft was on approach because the slats are only used when the plane is coming in to land,'' he said. The aircraft was taken to the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> maintenance base for repairs. The <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said that he did not know the age of the aircraft or the exact number of passengers on Flight 760.
