<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man who kept hospital workers at bay with a gun while tearfully removing his comatose son from life support systems and letting him die dramatized an ethical `` issue waiting to happen,'' a law professor says. <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Linares </PERSON>, 23, is charged with first-degree murder and on Thursday was ordered to undergo a psychiatric examination by a judge who called his case `` an extraordinary situation surrounded by extraordinary circumstances.'' `` I want to know if he is any danger to himself or anyone else,'' said Cook County Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bastone </PERSON>, before setting another hearing for May 18. <PERSON> Linares </PERSON>, free on $ 75,000 personal recognizance bond, refused to talk to reporters. Defense lawyer <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Scholz </PERSON> said <PERSON> Linares </PERSON>, who told police, `` I did it because I love my son,'' will plead innocent. <PERSON> Scholz </PERSON> met briefly with prosecutors today in the chambers of Chief Criminal Court Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON> and worked out an agreement to delay until May 3 the appearance dates for those subpoenaed, said <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION> Cook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>'s Attorney <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Partee </PERSON> Ms. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> would not comment further because of the confidentiality surrounding grand jury proceedings. But a law-enforcement source with knowledge of the case said <PERSON> Linares </PERSON>' wife and several other family members had received subpoenas to appear before the grand jury, possibly as early as today <PERSON> Partee </PERSON> on Thursday confirmed his intention to prosecute <PERSON> Linares </PERSON>, but suggested there could be `` a compassionate kind of justice.'' <PERSON> Partee </PERSON> said he could understand the emotions that a parent feels at seeing the suffering of an incurably ill child. `` But we must be reasonable and say, I think, that under no circumstances does any person have the right to take the life of another,'' he said during the Thursday taping of a radio show to be aired Sunday. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Epstein </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> law professor and fellow at the school's <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ethics </ORGANIZATION>, said that charging <PERSON> Linares </PERSON> with murder was wrong and called the case an `` issue waiting to happen.'' `` Doctors have an exaggerated sense of the sacred nature of life,'' <PERSON> Epstein </PERSON> said. `` It seems to me he should have been able to write a letter to the hospital saying, ` Please turn off the respirator. Very truly yours.''' Other ethicists also expressed sympathy for the father of two other children, who along with his wife had asked months ago for life support to be withdrawn from their 16-month old son, <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON>. The parents had been refused. The boy had been unconscious and not expected to recover since August, when he swallowed a balloon at a birthday party, said his physician, Dr. <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON>, director of pediatric intensive care at Rush-Presbyterian-St. <PERSON> Luke </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, where Wednesday's incident occurred <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON> said, `` I was personally and professionally sympathetic'' with the <PERSON> Linares </PERSON>' request to withdraw life support, but `` I did n't believe there was a legal option to allow me to act on the basis of their request.'' <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, legal counsel for the hospital, said that because of <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION>' child-abuse laws, the only way the institution could have complied would have been if <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> had been determined totally brain-dead or his heart and lungs had stopped functioning. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON>, director of the Center for Biomedical Ethics at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` I have sympathy for this father, because it seems to me he felt he had no choice but to act on what he felt was best for this child at the point of a gun. `` I still think he should be prosecuted. I do n't think you can use weapons to direct medical treatment,'' <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>. `` But I have sympathy because I think society has not made it possible for parents to be heard about when medical treatment should be stopped _ when it is futile _ for very young children,'' <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON> said. Police said <PERSON> Linares </PERSON> entered the hospital intensive care unit at about 1 a.m. Wednesday and unhooked the respirator of his son while holding hospital workers off with a .357 - caliber Magnum <PERSON> Linares </PERSON>, a house painter in <LOCATION> Cicero </LOCATION>, surrendered the gun as soon as he was sure the boy was dead, authorities said. His wife, <PERSON> Tamara </PERSON>, was out of the room at the time. Authorities said <PERSON> Linares </PERSON> also disconnected the respirator in December, but it was quickly replaced and he was not charged because the hospital did not call police.
