<HEAD>Party Readmits Chronicler of Stalin's Crimes After 20 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Communist Party has readmitted <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON>, a historian whose expose of the bloody dictatorial rule of <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> prompted his expulsion 20 years ago, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said Friday. <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON>, 63, said he reacted `` positively'' to the news. Asked in an interview if he attributed his restoration to President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms, he responded: `` I did n't change my views. A turnabout occurred in the party, the Central Committee. They stopped discriminating against me. I have been published here.'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> had asked the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to be restored as a party member, and the request was approved. But <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> he had not made any request. He said party officials approached him several months ago and asked if he wanted to become a member again. `` They asked me how I would react, and I said I would not object.'' <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> said he never considered asking to be restored as a party member during the rule of President <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> because, `` That was another epoch.'' <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> died in 1982. Like many Soviets who had fallen out of official favor for what once was considered dissent, <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> has gradually been restored to good graces. He has appeared at officially sponsored news conferences, been quoted frequently in the official press and was elected April 9 as a deputy to the new Soviet parliament, the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said it was <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON>'s book about <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s crimes, `` Let History Judge,'' that prompted his expulsion from the party in 1969, but that the control committee determined that action was `` unfounded'' and restored his membership. <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> has said `` Let History Judge,'' which he started writing in 1962, was `` the main work of my life.'' Seeing a possibility that <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> would be restored posthumously to official good graces despite his crimes, <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> decided to have the book published abroad. It came out in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and several other countries in 1971. But it was n't until this year that it appeared in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The literary journal <LOCATION> Znamya </LOCATION> published the first part of `` Let History Judge'' in its January issue. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Progress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION> is to put out the entire book, an indictment of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s dictatorial rule. Under <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of glasnost, or openness, it is no longer considered dissent to condemn <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> or report his crimes. In fact, the Soviet press is full of articles about <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s personality cult <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> has estimated that 40 million Soviets were either killed, arrested or otherwise repressed under <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, and his figure _ along with other of his remarks about <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> _ have appeared in the Soviet press. He believes _ as does <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> _ that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> can move toward a democratic political system without abandoning fundamental tenets of Marxism-Leninism. <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> and his brother, <PERSON> Zhores </PERSON>, were among the first prominent members of what evolved into the Soviet dissident movement. <PERSON> Zhores </PERSON> <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON>, a biochemist and gerontologist, was placed in a psychiatric hospital before he was forced to leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> in 1973. Human rights campaigner <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> has said <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> was an important influence on him, even though they later separated. After his expulsion from the party, authorities tolerated <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON>, and he became a valuable, unofficial source for journalists seeking information about Soviet history and politics.
