caused a panic during which victims were trampled to death as they tried to flee. Most of the victims were Italian. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> complied with the extradition request in September 1987, and the five-month trial began Oct. 17, 1988. Closing arguments ended March 20. Sir <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Livermore </PERSON>, one of the defense lawyers, said an appeal was likely. `` The acquittals are OK, but I am disappointed they've handed out custodial sentences to the others,'' he said. `` I do n't think they would have to serve more than between 10 and 12 months. But I was hoping the whole of their sentences would be suspended.'' Prosecutor <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Erauw </PERSON> said he saw no need to keep the 14 convicted fans behind bars pending appeal. `` I thought there was no need as most of them came to -LRB- Friday's -RRB- hearing,'' he told reporters, adding that unless an appeal is filed, the 14 `` will receive an invitation to come to prison.''
