<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 White House Chief of Staff <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> warned on Friday that higher interest rates could `` scrunch down'' the economy. `` It is a consumer issue to be worried about interest rates,'' as well as tax increases and international trade, <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> told a luncheon of Consumer Alert, a conservative group he once headed. <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> claimed for the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration the achievement of keeping the economic recovery going, saying: `` This economy is strong, it is robust, and it will continue to thrive as long as we do n't adopt policies to scrunch it down.'' `` Those policies,'' he added, `` include interest rates. Those of you who are wise consumers understand that when you go to buy a car or a house or anything that requires you as a consumer to pay over a long period of time, one of the most critical aspects of whether or not it's a good deal for you is the rate of interest you will have to pay on the purchase.'' President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said that he does not want the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, an independent body, to concentrate so hard on fighting inflation that it tips the economy into a recession. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has strong influence over interest rates through its control of the money supply, largely exercised through purchases and sales of government bonds, through rates it charges for use of its funds, and through other regulations. Fed credit policies are made public only with a time lag. The policy-making Open Market Committee decided in February not to increase rates further for the moment, but two weeks after that meeting the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> raised by one-half percentage point to 7 percent the rate it charges member banks for funds. The most recent figures show the economy expanding at an annual rate of 3 percent during the first three months of the year, and inflation as measured by consumer prices increasing at an annual rate of 6.1 percent during the first quarter, the highest rate in two years. <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> said the budget agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would bring a deficit reduction of $ 65 billion to $ 75 billion, and economic growth if it continues at the current rate would add $ 85 billion a year to federal revenue next year and the year after without new taxes. `` Compare that to what alternatives that are being proposed. One of the alternatives is a gasoline tax -LRB- increase -RRB-,'' he said. `` I think you all remember what happened when we had significant increases in gasoline prices in the late'70s. Our economy was stifled. ... If you want to match what you can get out of growth with a gasoline tax that would inhibit growth, you would have to be looking at an 85-cent per gallon increase. `` I ca n't imagine anyone advocating such a policy and getting away with being called a consumerist, and yet there are those who are trying to do that.'' He did not say who he had in mind. `` As a consumer you certainly worry about having competitive products in the market, and it is a consumer issue to have a strong commitment to free trade that allows competitive products to come in here,'' <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> said. `` And I think one of the most difficult consumer issues to deal with emotionally is the trade issue. Because sometimes the first reaction, the emotional reaction of exclusion, is not one in the best interests of consumer or the country,'' he said.
