<FIRST>r w AM-Physicians-Referrals     04-28 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Physicians-Referrals,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Suggests Arrangements May Help Drive Up Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A government report on Friday suggested that financial arrangements between physicians and health care businesses to which they refer Medicare patients may be helping to drive up costs in the federal health insurance program. The report to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>' inspector general found that one in seven <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> physicians has a financial interest in a health care business to which they refer their patients. It also found that patients of these physicians receive far more laboratory and other services than patients of physicians who have no financial arrangements with health care businesses. The report by Inspector General <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kusserow </PERSON> stopped short of saying that financial arrangements between physicians and laboratories and other health-related businesses lead to unnecessary testing and higher Medicare costs. `` While we have demonstrated an association rather than a causality, this finding ... is quite troubling,'' the report said. <PERSON> Kusserow </PERSON> recommends that the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> agency that oversees <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>, require health-care providers billing the program to disclose the names of their physician owners and investors to the program. He also recommends that all claims submitted for <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> payment contain the names of referring physicians. HHS is developing regulations that would limit referring-physicians' financial involvement in laboratories or clinics, and a bill introduced in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would generally prohibit physicians from referring <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> patients to health care businesses in which they hold a financial interest. Rep. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Stark </PERSON>, D-Calif., who introduced the legislation, said Friday in a statement that `` Medicare, patients, and the taxpayer are paying tens of millons of dollars for needless tests, caused by doctors referring patients to centers from which the doctor makes a profit because of the referral. `` If we do not stop this practice, and if it continues to spread, the added cost to <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> and the American health care system will be billions of dollars per year,'' <PERSON> Stark </PERSON> said. While many joint venture arrangements in the health-care industry are legitimate, <PERSON> Kusserow </PERSON>'s office is distributing 1.2 million copies of a fraud alert to the nation's health care providers warning that certain arrangements violate the <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> and Medicaid anti-kickback law. The report found that about 15 percent of physicians who bill <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> have an ownership, investment or compensation arrangement with health care businesses to which they refer patients. It estimated that 12 percent of physicians who bill <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> have ownership or investment interests in health care businesses, including testing laboratories, to which they refer patients. Eight percent of Medicare physicians have compensation arrangements with such businesses, including space rental and consulting agreements and management services contracts. Discounting the overlap between the two groups, about 15 percent have at least one or both types of financial interest. Also, at least 25 percent of independent clinical laboratories and 27 percent of independent physiological laboratories are owned wholly or partly by referring physicians, the report found. In addition, the report said that patients referred by physicians who own or invest in clinical laboratories received 45 percent more clinical lab services than all Medicare patients in general, regardless of where they received the services. This increased use of services cost the <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> program $ 28 million in 1987, the report said. `` Certainly the utilization effect we have seen in the laboratory industries is cause for concern to the Medicare program,'' the report said. The inspector general's office compiled its findings through surveys of about 3,680 physicians and 1,132 health care businesses as well as interviews with industry representatives and health care experts.
