<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two priceless fish fossils, estimated to be 300 million years old, are missing from a <ORGANIZATION> Bradley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> display case and officials said Friday they may have been stolen for a private collector. <PERSON> Merrill </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON>, chairman of the geological sciences department at <LOCATION> Bradley </LOCATION>, said he discovered the theft Tuesday. Police are investigating. `` We use them for educational purposes so we do n't want to keep them locked away in a vault,'' <PERSON> Foster </PERSON> said. Stolen were the remains of a `` jawless fish'' related to the lamprey family, and the remains of a bony, ray-finned fish. The two fossils were imbedded on four small pieces of rock. <PERSON> Foster </PERSON> said they were the rarest and most valuable specimens in <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>'s collection, which numbers in the hundreds of thousands of fossils. Jawless fish were prehistoric ancestors of contemporary fish and are thought to have evolved from sand-dwelling filter feeders about 450 million years ago, <PERSON> Foster </PERSON> said. A similar jawless fish fossil was stolen from the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION> about 10 years ago, he said. <PERSON> Foster </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> theft appeared to be the work of experts who pried open a jewelry-type glass display case. `` This was not your normal snatch thief,'' he said. `` To the average thief in <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>, these fossils are worthless. These were stolen by someone who really knows fossils well.'' <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Reinertsen </PERSON>, senior staff geologist for the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Survey </ORGANIZATION>, said collectors often buy and sell fossils through ads in mineral supply catalogs. `` There's a market for it,'' <PERSON> Reinertsen </PERSON> said. `` But if it's that rare, I suspect -LRB- it -RRB- was snagged for a private collection.''
