<HEAD>Court Upholds Dismissal Of Islanders Claim About Nuclear Tests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A three-member federal appeals court panel Friday upheld the dismissal of suits by <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islanders </ORGANIZATION> claiming damages from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nuclear tests. `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has stripped the courts of jurisdiction over these claims,'' declared the appeals court opinion by <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Sentelle </PERSON>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> ruled on June 16, 1987 that federal courts have no jurisdiction to assess the validity of an agreement giving the government of the <LOCATION> Marshall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> authority to press claims of citizens for damages from the atomic tests between 1946 and 1958. The <LOCATION> Marshall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1986 signed a <ORGANIZATION> Compact </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> giving the islands self-government status. A federal law was passed endorsing the compact. Under the independence settlement, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> gave the <ORGANIZATION> Marshall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islands </ORGANIZATION> goverment $ 150 million to pay people claiming damages from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nuclear tests in the 1940s and 1950s. The plaintiffs claim that sum is insufficient and are attempting to sue for more. On Aug. 22, 1983, while the compact and settlement were being negotiated, some 3,000 island residents directly downwind from the nuclear test sites filed suit in federal court. They sought damages for personal injuries and death resulting from their exposure to dangerous levels of radiation. Attorneys for the islanders had argued that the compact was invalid and that technically the islands are still a territory of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, under whose stewardship they operated for some 40 years. All three judges on the appeals panel affirmed the lower court ruling. However, <PERSON> Sentelle </PERSON> was alone in his conclusion that the challenge by the islanders raises a political question that was unreviewable by the courts. `` While the treaty power of the executive expressly involves the participation of the legislature, no where does the constitution contemplate the participation by the third, non-political branch, that is the judiciary,'' said <PERSON> Sentelle </PERSON>. Judge <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Starr </PERSON> did n't concur with that section of <PERSON> Sentelle </PERSON>'s decision, saying the matter is an unreviewable political question. Chief Judge <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Wald </PERSON> wrote a separate opinion. <PERSON> Wald </PERSON> argued that the <LOCATION> Marshall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> controversy falls outside the political question doctrine on the basis of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s consideration of questions with potentially substantial impact on foreign relations She also said: `` I am troubled by the majority's uncritical assumption that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> may deprive a narrow class of plaintiffs of judicial relief, even if their claims are nonconstitutional.'' <PERSON> Wald </PERSON> said the jurisdiction-stripping provisions of the compact and the `` espousal'' section settling nuclear testing claims `` were consistently thought of as parts of a package. `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> did not seriously consider enacting one without the other.'' She said that she believes <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> intended that withdrawing jurisdiction should be contingent on court approval of the espousal mechanism settling nuclear testing claims. She found that mechanism valid, saying: `` I do not believe ... that international law in any way forbids the agreement reached here.''
