<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new federal regulation goes into effect Saturday aimed at protecting consumers from used car sellers who change the odometer readings on cars. The rule implementing the 1986 Truth in Mileage Act requires that records be kept of automobile mileage and is intended to make it possible for a would-be buyer to trace the actual mileage of a vehicle. Although waivers have been given in several states that have said they need more time to change forms, the law requires that motor vehicle titles issued after Saturday must be printed so that counterfeiting and alterations can easily be detected. It also requires that mileage readings be disclosed on the title whenever the car is sold. If the title does not have a space for the odometer reading, a separate disclosure statement is required. Used car dealers, leasing companies and auto auctions must maintain records, including the mileage of vehicles sold, for at least five years. Federal laws prohibit tampering with odometers. In 1987, the latest year for which the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> has a complete report, 17 cases of large-scale odometer fraud were sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and five others to state enforcement agencies. Some of the cases led to civil action, and eight federal grand jury indictments led to 14 criminal convictions, said agency spokesman <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
