<HEAD>Violations strain cease-fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with shelling jeopardizing cease-fire.
Pickup 8th graf, `Aoun, who...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BEI1,4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A cease-fire negotiated by the Arab League was strained by repeated violations Friday, threatening a renewal of the shelling duels between Lebanese Christian and Syrian troops that killed 273 people. The truce that ended 52 days of bombardments also was jeopardized by differences of interpretation over who controls the ports _ the issue that started the fighting. A police spokesman said Syrians and their Druse Moslem allies fired sporadic salvos of rockets at the Christian port of <LOCATION> Byblos </LOCATION> from about 1:30 p.m. to nightfall, but no casualties were reported. The cease-fire went into effect at noon Friday. The spokesman said the Christian gunners did not retaliate. `` Infractions are so far of a minor nature, but they could collapse the cease-fire if they continue or intensify,'' said the spokesman, who was not identified in line with regulations. He also said that at about 1:30 p.m., two howitzer shells fired from Syrian-controlled mountains southeast of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> hit the Christian sector but caused no casualties. On Friday before the cease-fire began, Syrian troops and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> militiamen intermittently fired howitzer and mortar rounds across the Green Line that divides the capital into Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Christian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> east </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, police reported. They said there were no casualties. During the 52 days of frequently heavy shelling at least 993 people were wounded. The truce was announced Thursday at the end of an emergency meeting of <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> foreign ministers in <LOCATION> Tunis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION>. The agreement provides for an unspecified number of Arab observers to monitor the cease-fire, thus loosening <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s grip as <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s main powerbroker. The cease-fire is the fourth attempt by the 22-nation <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> to halt the fighting. It was welcomed by the main parties to the conflict _ <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Lebanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> army commander Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, who had declared a `` war of liberation'' from <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, called the truce `` the first step toward a broader pan-Arab role in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, which would weaken <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s monopoly of the decision-making process in our country.'' In <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, President <PERSON> Hafez </PERSON> <PERSON> Assad </PERSON>'s government said it is `` satisified with resolutions announced by the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>.'' <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> initially sent its 40,000 troops into <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in 1976 on a peacekeeping mandate from the league. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> supported the decision to send in Arab League observers. She added that outside parties involved in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> must exercise `` utmost restraint.'' Under questioning, Ms. <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said that statement was a reference to <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>. A <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> said <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> would meet Saturday with the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> committee that drafted the plan. The meeting follows a statement by the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> supporting the Arab League's peace efforts and urging that <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> `` make all possible efforts and ... contacts which could be deemed useful.'' The league truce calls for lifting the air, sea and land blockades imposed during the fighting. An earlier statement from <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s Cabinet welcomed `` lifting of blockades imposed on legal ports besieged by the Syrian forces.'' It said maritime agencies should `` instruct their ships to head to legal ports.'' <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> appears to be maintaining a blockade of ports run by Syrian-backed militias, a step likely to jeopardize the truce. Moslem army brigade commanders said the `` cease-fire and the lifting of blockades were a whole package agreement.'' The present confrontation broke out March 8, two days after <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> ordered a blockade of militia-run ports that deny the state treasury $ 100 million a year in customs dues. Druse warlord <PERSON> Walid </PERSON> <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON>'s militia retaliated by shelling the 310-square-mile Christian enclave. Syrian gunners joined. The <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lebanon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION>, the organ of the right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Phalange </ORGANIZATION> party, voiced concern the truce is `` mere security tranquilizers.'' The Syrian-backed Moslem Cabinet of acting Premier <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>, which competes with the <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> government in running <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, pledged `` full cooperation'' in the truce. It made no comment on <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s order Friday that <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> International Airport reopen. The country's only airport, located on the edge of Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, closed March 12 after Christian gunners targeted it. A source close to <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON> said the airport will stay closed until the Moslem Cabinet decides otherwise.
