<HEAD>Raul Sendic, Founder of Uruguay's Tupamaros Movement, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Sendic </PERSON>, founder of the extreme left <ORGANIZATION> Tupamaros </ORGANIZATION> movement in <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, died Friday in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, where he was undergoing treatment for a neurological illness, officials at the <PERSON> Edouard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rist </PERSON> clinic said. He was 63. Sendic long suffered from neurological problems believed to be the result of torture in Uruguayan prisons in the early 1970s. He had lived in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> for the past two years. <PERSON> Sendic </PERSON>'s tightly organized urban guerrilla cells were a model for Central American, Argentine and Chilean movements to follow. The cells used cleancut youths from old families to infiltrate the government they sought to topple. After 13 years in prison, <PERSON> Sendic </PERSON> was freed in 1985 along with many other political prisoners after the civilian government of President <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanguinetti </PERSON> replaced <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>'s military regime. Sendic organized strikes in the sugar cane fields and hunger marches in 1960-61, then changed to an urban guerrilla strategy with the founding in 1963 of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. The front is called the MLN by its Spanish initials but is better known as the <ORGANIZATION> Tupamaros </ORGANIZATION>, after <ORGANIZATION> Tupac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Amaru </ORGANIZATION>, an 18th-century Inca chief burned at the stake by the Spaniards. The Tupamaros raided food warehouses, redistributing their booty to the poor, and later moved into kidnappings for ransom to raise money. One such incident inspired the film `` State of Siege,'' by director <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gavras </LOCATION>, starring <PERSON> Yves </PERSON> <PERSON> Montand </PERSON> as the American advisor to the Uruguayan police who was kidnapped and later killed. The MLN's first legal convention was held in December 1985, where delegates voted to abandon armed struggle in favor of non-violent political action, with a Marxist and nationalist program favoring labor and land reform. Sendic was wounded and captured by soldiers in September 1972. He was held without trial for 12 years, during which his family and human rights campaigners protested the conditions of his detention. He was convicted and sentenced to 45 years in prison in 1984, but released the following year.
