<HEAD>Pinochet Says He Won't Run For President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Right-wing military President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> said Friday he definitely will not run in the Dec. 14 presidential election, but he said he will stay on as commander of the army. Gen. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, speaking at a news conference after swearing in two new ministers to his 16-member Cabinet, also proposed limited changes to the constitution written by the military. `` I feel a deep attachment to the constitution,'' <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> said, explaining why he will not run for president. The constitution prohibits him from seeking re-election, but several right-wing groups have insisted in recent months that a formula be found to allow him to run. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> himself previously hinted that he could agree. On Tuesday, he told a group of labor leaders who asked him to run again: `` That does not depend on me, but on you. I am prepared for anything.'' He stressed that he will hand power to the winner in the December election, which he was obliged to call after voters in a referendum last October rejected a military proposal to extend his term until 1997. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> said Friday that after leaving the presidency, he will remain as commander of the army, which the constitution allows him to do. `` Under the present circumstances, I think that's the position where I can serve my country best,'' <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> said. Opposition parties and even some government supporters repeatedly have criticized <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s decision to remain head of the army, which has been his power base since he seized power in a violent 1973 coup. Critics said his continuation in the nation's top military position would threaten the stability of the future civilian government. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s decision this week to keep Interior Minister <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Caceres </PERSON> was seen by some opposition leaders as an indication that he was finally accepting the constitutional changes sought by opposition and pro-government parties. But on Friday, he made clear that he is offering only limited changes. At the news conference, he listed six possible amendments, far less that those sought by the opposition. He said he is prepared to change an article banning Marxism, to ease the mechanism for future constitutional changes, to drop the presidential power to disband the lower house of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and to send citizens into exile; to shorten the eight-year presidential term, and to change the makeup of a powerful military dominated <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. He rejected changes sought by the opposition, including a clause that makes nine members of the 26-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> appointed instead of elected, and another that prevents the future civilian government from firing the heads of the three branches of the armed forces and the national police. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> appointed <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Salame </PERSON>, a chemistry teacher, to replace <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Guzman </PERSON> as education minister; and <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON>, a mining engineer, to replace <PERSON> Pablo </PERSON> <PERSON> Baraona </PERSON> as minister of mines.
