<HEAD>Services Set Saturday For Federal Judge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Funeral services are scheduled Saturday for controversial <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON>, who went into semi-retirement 14 years ago after a stormy 32-year career on the bench. <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> died Thursday at age 89 after a short bout with pneumonia and a long battle with a bleeding ulcer, his family said. He had been hospitalized about two weeks. <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> was born Sept. 13, 1899, in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>. He received his law degree from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> in 1922 and was a private attorney in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> when President <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> put him on the federal bench in 1943. <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> often feuded with other federal judges. In 1962, he testified before a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee that he was afraid of being poisoned, that his telephone was tapped and that his fellow judges sometimes cursed him. Twice he was removed from hearing multi-million-dollar lawsuits because of alleged personal interest or alleged bias and prejudice. He was indicted by a state grand jury in 1965 for allegedly conspiring to have a road on property he owned paved by the county. The criminal charge later was dismissed. In 1965, the 10th <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judicial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> stripped him of his powers for a month, contending he was `` unable or unwilling to discharge efficiently the duties of his office.'' He was embroiled in a libel suit with one attorney and once disbarred the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney and five other federal attorneys in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> from practicing in