 `` If the fixes are simple, we can maintain the possibility of a Monday afternoon launch,'' he said. `` If we have to replace the pump or the -LRB- fuel -RRB- line, we could go well into next week.'' <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said the first goal of the launch team was to `` get the crew safely out of there'' by making certain all systems were stable. The astronauts reset switches in the cabin before taking the elevator to the base of the pad for a trip back to their crew quarters. The astronauts _ Walker, pilot <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Grabe </PERSON> and mission specialists <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Cleave </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> and <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Thagard </PERSON> _ returned to crew quarters. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> had set Atlantis' liftoff between 2:24 p.m. and 2:47 p.m., a narrow window dictated by the need to deploy the <ORGANIZATION> Magellan </ORGANIZATION> payload from a precise location above the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> and a requirement that the shuttle go before darkness fell at emergency landing sites in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>. The space agency must send <ORGANIZATION> Magellan </ORGANIZATION> on its way between April 28 and May 28 because that is when <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Venus </PERSON> are in proper alignment. If the spacecraft can not be launched by the end of May, officials would have to wait two years before the two planets again are in the desired position. The countdown had been almost flawless until the last minute. The only snag was a problem with a range-safety tracking computer that set back the count six minutes. `` All systems were ready to support a launch until we hit that unexpected problem,'' <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said. When Atlantis is launched, the astronauts are to release <ORGANIZATION> Magellan </ORGANIZATION> from the cargo bay and start it on a 450-day, 806-million-mile journey to <PERSON> Venus </PERSON>. It will be the first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> planetary flight in 11 years. The 7,600-pound spacecraft is to loop into orbit around <LOCATION> Venus </LOCATION> in August 1990 and map up to 90 percent of the surface with a high-resolution radar system that will pierce the planet's sulfuric acid clouds. The photos could disclose much about the history of <PERSON> Venus </PERSON> and why it evolved so differently than its sister planet <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, even though scientists believe they were almost identical at the formation of the solar system 4.6 billion years ago.
