pill to the state. <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON>'s repeated statements that the state refused to approve the use of chemical dispersants soon after the spill were `` demonstrably false.'' The statements have been repeated in the national news media and by federal officials, including <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON>, giving them increased credibility, <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said. `` If an untrue statement continues to be repeated time after time after time after time, and you do n't make an effort to refute that statement, then people will believe it like it was gospel. Obviously, that's happening now,'' he said. `` The fact is Exxon did not have the capability to carry out any kind of oil recovery that was very effective,'' <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelso </PERSON>, the state's chief environmentalist said. <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> fired back at the governor late Friday, accusing him in turn of spreading wrong information. In a letter to <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON>, a copy of which was obtained by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> had enough dispersants on hand and en route to `` contain the spill and significantly mitigate the impact of the oil on the shoreline.'' An <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION> mountain climber, meanwhile, took his own protest to an eight-story office building in <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION> where <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> has offices. <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION> police said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tumey </PERSON> climbed out on the roof of the building and rappelled down, stopping at about the fourth floor to attach a banner that read: `` Oil Spilled, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> Kills, Remember