<HEAD>Timber Industry Owly About Talking With `Enviros' Over Threatened
Species</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Timber industry officials angrily accused environmentalists Friday of using threats against the spotted owl as a propaganda `` hoax,'' and promised to mount a national effort to preserve forest lands for logging. The statements at a news conference appeared to dampen efforts by members of the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s congressional delegation and environmentalists to negotiate a way to protect both logging jobs and the endangered owl. Prodded by environmentalists, the federal Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> this week recommended listing the Northern spotted owl, which inhabits forests from northern <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, as a `` threatened'' species. That would involve preserving a large number of acres of old-growth forest for the approximately 1,500 breeding pairs of owls left. Each pair would require as much as 2,200 acres under a draft <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> plan. Industry officials, however, contend that action could result in as many as 280,000 job layoffs. Losses could reach $ 6.2 billion in payrolls, $ 900 million in payments to local counties and $ 3 billion in timber receipts to the federal treasury, said the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's warfare between the preservationists and the industry,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickell </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Contract </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loggers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. He accused `` enviros'' of using the spotted owl issue to bring logging in old growth forests to a halt. `` By the time all these studies -LRB- on owl populations -RRB- are done, five years from now, I think we'll find that this is the biggest hoax that's ever been pulled on the American public,'' he said. `` But by that time if these -LRB- timberland -RRB- set-asides are allowed to continue, the devastation to the industry and the <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> economy will be equivalent to that <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> bomb.'' <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuehne </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION>, said the industry was forming a national group called the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resource </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>. He said it would battle environmentalist efforts to make inroads against logging in all areas of the country, and would back up industry efforts to seek federal legislation designating lands for logging. <PERSON> Kuehne </PERSON> said the industry would only sit down to the negotiating table over the spotted owl issue as part of national talks pitting environmental issues against timber issues. The forest industry officials' estimates of damage to the timber industry were disputed by <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Durning </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Wilderness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>'s office in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> `` I am distressed with the exaggerated claims ... of job losses and money losses to the economy that the industry has been making,'' she said. She said a society report last fall concluded that only 2,300 jobs would be lost over the next 40 years if significant stands of old-growth timber were set aside to save the owls. At the same time, she said, 26,500 jobs would be lost due to mill modernization. `` Conservationists recognize that achieving a healthy economy for the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s timber-dependent area is part of the picture by which we will also achieve protection for ancient forests,'' she said. The news conference followed a meeting between Reps. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Swift </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Wash </LOCATION>., and <PERSON> Sid </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, R-Wash., and more than two dozen representatives of the timber Both congressmen expressed hope that the differing sides could begin meetings to resolve the owl issue. `` I think it's essential to work with them and see what we can come up with,'' said <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>. However, many at the meeting expressed doubt the industry could make any headway against the environmentalists' position, noting that court decisions have locked up some owl habitat forestlands, at least temporarily.
