<HEAD>Six Kuwaiti Tankers Deflagged by United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> agreed to remove the American flag from six Kuwait-owned oil tankers that sailed under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> protection during the Iraq-Iran war in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, officials said Friday. The decision, announced by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maritime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, ended two months of deadlock between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> officials over what had been assumed to be a routine matter when first announced last February. According to official sources in the gulf and in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <PERSON> Kuwaitis </PERSON> objected to a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> legal provision stipulating that even after the vessels reverted to Kuwaiti registry, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would retain the right to requisition them for use in a national emergency. The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> officials rejected such a condition as infringing on <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> sovereignty. They said the two sides finally agreed that the tankers would be returned to <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> rather than to the <ORGANIZATION> Kuwait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tanker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which actually operates them. Although the tanker company is wholly government-owned, the sources said, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials deemed the distinction sufficient for a waiver of <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s obligation to make the ships available to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Oates </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maritime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, said he could not comment other than to say the agreement became effective as of Thursday. Kuwaiti officials were not available to comment. The six ships include two petrolem product tankers and four identical liquefied gas carriers. They were among 11 Kuwait-owned tankers reflagged by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in mid-1987, entitling them to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> naval escort. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> at that time was attacking Kuwaiti shipping because of <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s support for <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in the war. Hostilities ended last Aug. 20 with a U.N.-mediated cease-fire. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> had set up a new company, the <ORGANIZATION> Chesapeake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Dover </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Del. </LOCATION>, as ostensible <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> owners of the tankers. <PERSON> Chesapeake </PERSON> will `` sell'' the six ships back to <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> in a transaction existing only on paper, the sources said. The other five tankers will continue to fly the Stars and Stripes, at least until next February, on condition that all-American crews replace the regular crews during that period. At the time of the reflagging in 1987, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration waived a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law requiring U.S.-flagged ships to have all-American crews.
