<HEAD>Adv for Thu PMs May 4 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Government Fights Misconceptions as Concern About AIDS Grows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The widely publicized death of a prostitute has increased concern about AIDS, and officials are trying to dispel false ideas about the disease in a nation where sex is a flourishing trade. Officials say at least 22 people in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> have developed active AIDS cases and 100 have been identified as carriers of the virus that causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome. Sixty-one of the 100 carriers are female prostitutes and 50 of them work near Clark Air Base and the Subic Bay naval base, the two huge <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military installations in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. Dr. <PERSON> Erlinda </PERSON> <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON>, the national AIDS registrar, believes the true figures are higher. She says inadequate testing and reporting methods may be missing 90 percent of the carriers. Since 30 per cent of carriers develop symptoms of the disease in five years, She fears AIDS cases could reach 300 by then. Acquired immune deficiency syndrome, for which there is no cure, weakens the body's ability to resist infection and makes the victim vulnerable to a range of fatal illnesses. It is spread by sexual contact, use of infected needles and contaminated blood products. Officials say all but three of the 22 AIDS patients acquired the disease abroad. Two of the three who contracted it in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> have died. A male homosexual died last year and the second victim was a 24-year-old bar girl from <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, home of <ORGANIZATION> Clark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>. Her death last month was widely publicized. She died at the time of newspaper reports that a young Brazilian woman, who claimed to have had sex with many prominent Filipinos, tested positive for the AIDS virus. The Brazilian has left the country and, because of privacy regulations, health officials refuse to confirm whether she was infected. Officials say AIDS could spread rapidly in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> because of prostitution and public misconceptions of the disease. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Resurrecion </PERSON> of the national AIDS control program, said a Gallup survey of 35 nations had the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> among the countries whose people believe the disease can be contracted by working beside infected people or sharing drinking glasses with them, or from insect bites. A survey by the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> found that many male prostitutes thought exercise prevents AIDS, he said. Officials say 94 percent of men who contracted AIDS or carried the virus had not used condoms. Health Department workers are studying ways to combat AIDS myths and are instructing the public on effective precautions. Officials plan to spend most of the $ 467,290 allocated for AIDS control on print and broadcast advertising. `` Our basic goal is to change the behavior of people, considering that each individual has the responsibility to protect himself,'' Dr. <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, city health officer <PERSON> Proceso </PERSON> <PERSON> Mejia </PERSON> said posters saying `` Prevent AIDS, Use Condoms'' and `` No Condom, No Sex'' were placed in the bar district. The high percentage of AIDS carriers among prostitutes working near <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bases has led some women's groups to urge that the installations be closed to keep the disease from spreading. `` We think AIDS is coming to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> through the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bases,'' said <PERSON> Adul </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Leon </PERSON>, an official of the militant feminist organization <PERSON> Gabriela </PERSON>, which demands that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> finance AIDS control programs. Dr. <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON> said the high incidence around the bases may be traceable to the fact that, since <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities paid for the program, 67 per cent of the 108,000 screened were from those areas. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have promised that any <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> service member found to carry the virus will not be assigned to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
