<HEAD>Major Events in Soviet-Chinese Relations Since 1949</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Lessons from China, b0671</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a chronology of major events in Chinese-Soviet relations since the People's Republic of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> was established in 1949: _ October 1949: The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was the first foreign nation to recognize the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> led by <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON> _ December 1949: <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> mades his first trip to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and was snubbed by <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, who met the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> revolutionary only after <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> threatened to return home _ February 1950: After difficult negotiations, <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> signed a friendship treaty _ 1955: The Soviets left <LOCATION> Dalian </LOCATION>, or <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arthur </LOCATION>, which they had occupied since Wo _ February 1956: <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>'s speech criticizing <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, who died in 1953, surprised and angered the Chinese They accused the Soviets of rerld War II. visionism. _ October 1957: The Soviets agreed to furnish <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> with a sample atomic bomb The promise was retracted two years later after relations began to cool. _ 1958: <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> to urge caution toward the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s conflict with <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> over the offshore islands of <LOCATION> Quemoy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Matsu </LOCATION>, but was rebuffed _ October 1959: <PERSON> Khrushschev </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> for the 10th anniversary of the People's Republic Talks with <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> went badly and ref the campaign, which began last year. Unlike the dozens of other national academies in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, the American Academy receives no direct government financing. It does apply for and receive some federal grants. `` The endowment was great when <PERSON> McKim </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> J.P. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vanderbilt </PERSON> and others put it together in the early 1900s and it was n't bad in the 1940s and 50s,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Connors </PERSON>, the new academy director. `` But as of the 70s and 80s it began to look very insignificant to the needs of the academy. After the drop in the dollar in 1985, it's been very hard for us to pay our bills.''. Keeping all the academy's fellows happy also has been difficult. They find the modest stipends for a year of study and work do not go far in one of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s most expensive cities. Stipends range from less than $ 6,000 to $ 11,000 plus a room, studio and daily meal at the academy. This year's literature fellow, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON>, said he would have stayed home had not the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION>, where he teaches, supplemented his stipend of about $ 8,000. A predecessor, novelist <PERSON> Padgett </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, left the academy early because he could not afford to stay. `` It's difficult to live on the stipend if you're alone, very difficult if you have a spouse and impossible if you have a family,'' said <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON>, 39, who brought his wife and child. Criticism from the outside also crops up now and then. There have been complaints, which <PERSON> Connors </PERSON> rejects, that the academy is isolated, overlooks <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> in both senses of the word and is a clubby institute little known beyond the Janiculum. <PERSON> Connors </PERSON>, a 44-year-old art and architecture historian from <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, says he is trying to improve the financial and living conditions for fellows. He said the lowest stipend will be raised next year from $ 5,800 to $ 7,500 and he hopes to arrange apartment suites for families. Many fellows would like better food in the academy dining hall, which they say suits a college cafeteria more than a city renowned for cuisine, but most agree with <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON> that the academy's benefits far outweigh the hardships. `` Aside from more money for the fellowships and higher quality of food, it's hard to know what the academy can do better,'' he said. `` Being in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> has affected me as a writer. Americans have a poor sense of history and you ca n't walk around <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> without being immersed in history. `` It's inspiring, drinking at a cafe where <PERSON> Goethe </PERSON> drank and standing in the cemetery where <PERSON> Keats </PERSON> is buried. ... There's no doubt I'll be writing about <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> in one way or the other for many years to come.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Obuck </PERSON>, a 41-year-old painter from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said he sometimes misses the razzle-dazzle <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> art scene but loves the soft Roman light. `` It's so different from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` I have a studio with a huge skylight so I can paint in the daylight. I do n't know how I'll ever go back to artificial light. Each year, the academy selects about 25 fellows from 1,000 applicants. They are chosen by a jury of prominent artists and scholars in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on the basis of submitted works, proposed projects and interviews. A few resident and visiting scholars also stay at the academy for a few months to work on their own projects and counsel younger fellows. This year, they have included <PERSON> Brodsky </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> <PERSON> Salisbury </PERSON>. Most fellows live and work in the main building, a palazzo of marble and faded red stucco built at the turn of the century. Academy directors and visitors normally live up the road at the <LOCATION> Villa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aurelia </LOCATION>, a 17th century palace in landscaped gardens and ilex trees that was <PERSON> Garibaldi </PERSON>'s headquarters during the battle with the French in 1849. The academy library, considered one of the world's finest for classical studies and archaeology, is open to the public and attracts many researchers. Fellows generally are left on their own to pursue their projects. There are no courses, exams or graduation ceremonies. In the spring, the artists have a public exhibit, the scholars give lectures and the composers present a concert.
