<FIRST>s a BC-BlackFarmers Adv07-2Takes   04-28 1183</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Black Farmers, Adv 07-2 Takes,1214</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 7, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Black Farmers Battle Odds To Survive</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Story is complete in one take; optional add for editors desiring
more detail</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Spring has kissed central <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, and L.C. <PERSON> Crosby </PERSON> once again is busy planting corn, peas, butter beans and okra. He's also hoping for a bumper watermelon crop this summer. `` I've got a plan,'' he says as he leans against his old <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> tractor. `` If it works out, I'm going to get my watermelons on the market two or three weeks earlier than anybody else and I'll clean up.'' <LOCATION> Crosby </LOCATION>, a friendly man with a wiry build, becomes excited as he talks about his crops and the 43-acre `` dream farm'' where he and his family once worked as field hands. However, this could be the last spring for his dream, and for a lot of other dreams like his. At 33, L.C. <LOCATION> Crosby </LOCATION> is a young, black farmer. And, as such he's twice as likely to lose his land as his white counterpart In 1910, the nation's 950,000 black farmers comprised 14 percent of all farmers in this country. Now, the remaining 35,000 make up just 1.6 percent of the 2.3 million farmers in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. According to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>, the number of black farms declined by 42 percent between 1978 and 1982. White farms fell by only 2.4 percent during the same period. `` Unless this trend is reversed, there will be no more black farmers in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> by the year 2,000.'' This dire prediction is contained in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'s 1982 report on the `` Decline of Black Farmers in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' Yet, while there's just a relative handful of young, black farmers still operating _ the current, median age for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> black farmers is 60 _ the federal government is trying to force L.C. <PERSON> Crosby </PERSON> off his land. `` The <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Farmer </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- has given him notice to vacate the premises because he's behind on his loan. But we're telling him to stay put and fight,'' says <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Paris </PERSON><PERSON> , </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a field coordinator for the private, non-profit Federation of Southern Cooperatives <PERSON> Crosby </PERSON> bought his farm, which includes a large pond and five-acre pecan orchard, at an <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> auction in 1985. He bid $ 36,500, borrowing $ 31,000 from the government. `` My annual payment is $ 3,800,'' he said. `` I fell behind the second year. Now, I've got the money to make the payment but the <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> wants the whole $ 30,000.'' <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> said he's heard that a wealthy white landowner, whose bid was $ 10,000 lower than Crosby's, covets the property. `` It's the same old story,'' he said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> is slowly changing but basically, at the local level, quite often its still a bunch of good ol' white boys who look after each other.'' <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>' father, who worked for the <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> for nearly 30 years and was one of the first black men ever to serve as an assistant county supervisor, agrees with this assessment. `` It was tragic. Blacks always got the last and the least,'' said the elder <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, adding that he saw hundreds of black Alabamians lose their farms during the 30 years he workd for the <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION>. `` I remember one time back, in the'60s, I was told, outright, by a white <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> committee member in <LOCATION> Bullock </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, that a black farmer had been denied a loan because he was ` shooting off his mouth about civil rights.''' Under the <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION>'s loan procedure, a county supervisor makes a recommendation to a three-member county loan committee, which then either approves or denies the loan. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, a 73-year-old farmer in the Mt. Zion community, near <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION>, was the first black ever to serve on an <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> county committee. In this country, the average black-owned farm contains fewer than 100 acres, compared with an average of 440 acres for all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farms. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Lena </PERSON> own 500 acres, which they slowly acquired over the past 40 years, parcel by parcel. `` My grandfather came to this area at age 12, shortly after he was freed from slavery,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. `` He never owned land, being a cash renter, but I've found that, for a black man in this country, there is no greater security, nor better avenue to independence, than farming.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, who said he and his four brothers pooled their resources and `` pulled together toward a common objective,'' acknowledged he is worried and saddened that this generation of young blacks is n't going into agriculture. `` After the Civil War, the federal government promised the freed blacks 40 acres and a mule but hardly any of them got it,'' he said. `` Our people should realize by now that they've got to help themselves; nobody's going to do it for them. `` I'm very concerned that young blacks are turning their backs on farming, at a time when life in the cities is getting worse every day.'' The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit advocacy group based in <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, estimates there now are fewer than 200 full-time black farmers, aged 25 or under, in the entire country. Officials at <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> A </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, who say they are getting 25 percent fewer agriculture students than they did 20 years ago, blame farming's poor image and the enormous difficulty young blacks face in amassing capital. The continuing phenomenon of black land loss was the topic at a recent meeting sponsored by the university and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION>. `` Greed and institutional racism'' are the major reasons blacks have been forced out of farming said the Rev. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Shelby </PERSON> <PERSON> Rooks </PERSON>, director of the church's <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homeland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministries </ORGANIZATION>, in his keynote address at the conference in <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C </LOCATION>. In its report, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> found that blacks were being ill-served by the <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>'s agency designed specifically to help poor farmers. The commission, noting that black farmers _ 90 percent of whom are in the South _ often are unable to deal with the ever more complex federal loan programs. The commission called for serious government intervention. Last July, as part of an omnibus farm bill passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> launched its `` Socially Disadvantaged Outreach Farm Ownership Program.'' `` So far,'' said <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Nolan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kegley </PERSON>, `` we have made 58 loans to minority farmers under the program.'' He said the loans, totalling $ 4.6 million, are to finance farm purchases for poor blacks and other minorities. `` We recognize the problems of the past and we're working on them at all levels,'' <PERSON> Kegley </PERSON> said. `` Since 1984 the percentage of <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> loans to blacks has been steadily increasing.'' He acknowledged, when asked, however, that only 91 of the <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION>'s 1,849 county supervisors are black In <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, the state with the most black farmers, eight of the 82 county supervisors are black. In <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, it's only three of 79. <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> officials in those states say they have had little luck recruiting qualified blacks because the goverment pay scale is n't competitive
</TEXT>
