<HEAD>GREENVILLE, Ala.: isn't competitive.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 In <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, however, eight of 57 county supervisors are black, two of seven district supervisors are black and 49 of 203 county committee members are black. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Paris </PERSON> says the <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> must make such across-the-board efforts in every state if black farmers are to have an equal chance to survive. The new <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> minority funding outreach program does little, he said, to help many of those black farmers already indebted to the federal government. `` If they really want to help black farmers they should forgive their past debts and let them start over,'' he added. `` Lord knows the <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> has done little enough in the past to help small farmers.'' <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>' organization is in the forefront of the effort to help black farmers stay on the land. The federation offers counseling in crop planning and farm management. It also helps poor farmers, black and white, wade through the intracacies of the <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> loan and appeal procedures. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Pennick </PERSON>, who heads the federation's Land Assistance Fund, has helped draft a proposed `` Minority Farmer's Act'' that would provide emergency aid. Among other things, it would create a special agency within the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> to deal with concerns of minority farmers and develop a special debt restructuring program for farmers who are less than $ 100,000 in hock to the <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION>. `` We hope to get the bill introduced this fall or early next year,'' <PERSON> Pinnock </PERSON> said. `` The black congressional caucus is planning to push it. We also have assurances of support support from some white congressmen.'' Black farmers such as L.C. <LOCATION> Crosby </LOCATION>, meanwhile, are hanging on by a slender thread. For others, such as <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Pigford </PERSON>, a ruined third-generation farmer from <LOCATION> Arcadia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, the thread has snapped. `` I have n't farmed since 1984, the year the hurricane blew through here,'' said <PERSON> Pigford </PERSON>, who now works in a factory. `` The <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> never would loan me enough money to buy a farm, just enough to rent out land to farm. But the hurricane ruined me and now the government is trying to take my house.'' <PERSON> Pigford </PERSON>, who testified in 1984 before a congressional committee investigating the <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION>'s lending practices, added that he thinks his chances are slim of ever getting back onto a tractor seat. Another young farmer, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Ammans </PERSON>, who raises turkeys at <LOCATION> Kenansville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, says whites should n't think that black farmers are just looking for free handouts. `` Like bald eagles I'm a member of an endangered species,'' he said. `` If the government is willing to help eagles, it oughta be willing to help me. All I want is a chance to survive.''
