<FIRST>r f PM-TradeReport     04-28 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trade Report,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasury Says South Korea and Taiwan Should Do More on Currencies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> need to do more to allow their currencies to rise in relation to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar as a way of lowering huge trade surpluses the two nations are running with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, according to a government report. The report the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sent to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday followed six months of negotiations the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has held with both countries. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been pressuring the nations to allow their currencies to rise in value in relation to the dollar as a way of making their products more expensive on American markets and making <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods cheaper in their markets. While saying that both nations have made some progress in boosting the value of their currencies, the report contended that much more needs to be done. The department said it would press forward with the negotiations in the hope of achieving further progress. The negative findings were likely to increase pressure on the two governments in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, where lawmakers have long been unhappy with the trade practices of the two nations. Last October, an initial <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> report had singled out <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> for `` manipulating'' their currencies to gain an unfair competitive advantage in world markets. <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> have for many years used part of the money earned through their trade surpluses to buy and sell currencies on the open market to have an impact on the price of their own currencies in relation to the dollar. By keeping their currencies from rising as much against the dollar as other currencies have, they have been able to keep the prices of their exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from rising. The practice has also made it harder for American industry to take advantage of a cheaper dollar in selling goods to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. In 1988, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had a merchandise trade deficit of $ 9.5 billion with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and $ 13 billion with <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, meaning that the two countries accounted for 18 percent of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s total trade deficit last year. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Report to the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on International Economic and Exchange Rate Policy,'' said that the assessment six months ago that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit would continue to improve this year had been clouded by recent developments, such as rising oil prices. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> did not forecast a new trade figure. However many private analysts fear that the trade deficit, which dropped dramatically in 1988 because of the decline of the value of the dollar against many major currencies, could even begin rising again unless the dollar fell further. The report was prepared under a provision of the Trade Act of 1988 which requires the administration to look for cases of currency manipulation by American competitors in world trade and to embark on bilateral negotiations to halt such practices.
</TEXT>
