<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar was stable in thin European trading today as the market settled down before a long holiday weekend. Gold prices were lower. Traders said they expected the dollar to stay in a narrow trading range unless the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> index of leading indicators, the only significant economic news to be announced today, turned out to be a surprise. Most traders expected the index, which was scheduled for release this afternoon, to show a drop in March of about 0.5 percent, following a decline of 0.3 percent in February. They said the dollar had appeared to have found a new trading range for the time being. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one British pound cost $ 1.6922, more expensive for buyers than $ 1.6905 late Thursday. Other dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Thursday's rates, included: 1.8763 West German marks, up from 1.8756; 1.6625 Swiss francs, up from 1.6585; 6.3440 French francs, down from 6.3455; 2.1155 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1150; 1,373.25 Italian lire, down from 1,373.50; and 1.1895 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1940 Earlier, the dollar rose in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> to 132.49 Japanese yen from 132.05 yen at Thursday's close. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar edged up further to 132.70 yen. Gold fell in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> to $ 380.50 a troy ounce, from $ 384.25 late Thursday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the metal opened at $ 381.50 a troy ounce, down from a $ 384.25 late Thursday. At mid-morning, the city's bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 381.30. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold closed at $ 382.89, lower than $ 385.71 Thursday. Silver bullion dipped in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to $ 5.63 a troy ounce, down from $ 5.76 bid late Thursday.
