<FIRST>a f BC-TickerTalk Adv01   04-28 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 01,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday May 1</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Bull Market Comeback?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Did the great bull market on Wall Street secretly survive the crash of 1987? Has it now, as in some science-fiction movie sequel, crawled out of the disaster's rubble and begun to prowl the canyons of Wall Street once more? Those questions are being raised in many investors' minds as the rally in stock prices that began in the waning weeks of 1987 carries to new high after new high. As of late last week the Dow Jones industrial average stood nearly 700 points, or 40 percent, above its low on Black Monday Oct 19, 1987. A 40 percent rise in 18 months compares pretty favorably with many a past rally that earned the `` bull market'' stamp. As if to confirm its status, the economy has kept growing at a robust rate, showing scarcely any effects from a very scary financial event. But one prominent money manager contends that people who think this way might be falling into a dangerous trap. If you judge the stock market by price alone, the bull appears to have revived, concedes <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gailliot </PERSON>, senior vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which manages assets totaling $ 37 billion. When you apply other traditional criteria, however, `` it does n't look at all like a bull market,'' <PERSON> Gailliot </PERSON> said in an interview In a bull market, he says, a broad array of stocks should be rising to keep pace with the narrow sample represented by the Dow Jones industrials. But that has n't been happening. While the averages have hit new post-crash highs, the number of individual stocks at new 52-week peaks has been unimpressive, he adds. `` Volume is not rising with price,'' he also observes. `` The rally to date continues to have the characteristics of a bear market rally. We expect a new low -LRB- below DJIA 1740 -RRB- in price before this bear market is over.'' For some time now <PERSON> Gailliot </PERSON>, like many other economists, has been predicting a recession that has yet to give any sign of showing up. What has confounded the forecasters, he says, has been persistent strength in spending by consumers, long since overextended by the usual yardsticks. Since consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of economic activity, `` the consumer is the ` gorilla' of our economy,'' he observes. `` If you do n't get the consumer right, you do n't get the business cycle right.'' Consumers' ability to keep spending has been stretched in the 1980s, <PERSON> Gailliot </PERSON> says, by devices such as low - -LRB- or no - -RRB- rate auto financing and home equity lines of `` These are marvelous innovations that do nothing but let the consumer go farther out on the limb.'' At some point, he says, consumers will reach the stage where they want or are forced to retrench. `` When the gorilla decides how much is enough,'' he says, `` then you get a recession.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon May 1</NOTE>
