<HEAD>Ag Panel Wants to Query Administration on Idled Export Program</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs grafs 9-12, Meanwhile, the ... agreement, with 5 grafs
to clarify and explain the meeting with Soviets and the sales figures for
wheat and other commodities.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> may subpoena <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration officials as part of its inquiry into why a popular program that subsidizes food exports has apparently been halted with no official notice. Though the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> denies that the Export Enhancement Program has been stopped, no sales using it have been completed since February. And lawmakers allege that a just-announced grain sale to the Soviets will be unsubsidized. `` Since the program started there has never been a two-month hiatus,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON>, D-Kan., who heads the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on wheat, soybeans and feed grains The holdup appears to be with the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>, where officials say a review of the program is taking place. When <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> representatives failed to appear before his subcommittee Thursday, <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON> said he may have subpoena them. He said the administration's budget writers first would be given a chance to answer questions in writing, but would be expected to `` respond quickly and satisfactorily.'' <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> <PERSON> Shipp </PERSON>, press secretary to <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>, said the program has slowed down because of weather and stock conditions and because there is a new administration, but it has not been suspended. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Scully </PERSON>, associate director for legislative affairs at <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION>, said director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> could n't make the hearing because he had another obligation and no other policymaker at the budget office was qualified to speak. Meanwhile, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced Thursday that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, will be allowed to purchase 24 million metric tons of grain this year instead of the 20 million previously negotiated. Lawmakers said the additional sales will not be subsidized. Only wheat has been subsidized in the grain sales to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Huge amounts of corn have been sold to the Soviets without subsidies. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> also said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet negotiators concluded a two-day meeting about commodity purchases under a long-term grain agreement that specifies regular sales of grain and soybeans during the year. The pact calls for such meetings twice a year. In a separate announcement, <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has bought an additional 150,000 tons of corn, which boosted total Soviet purchases of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn to 13.4 million tons. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> also has bought 4 million tons of wheat for delivery through Sept. 30, the end of the agreement's sixth year. According to <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>, the Soviets also have bought 450,000 tons of soybeans, nearly 1.4 million tons of soybean meal and 507,400 tons of grain sorghum for 1988-89 delivery. But a member of <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON>'s subcommittee said the Soviets went away from negotiations angry. The Soviets wanted to expand the amount to 30 million tons under the Export Enhancement Program, but were told their purchases would have to be unsubsidized, said Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagle </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Iowa </LOCATION>. Attempts to contact Soviet officials at their embassy in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> were unsuccessful. <PERSON> Shipp </PERSON> said the agreement does not stipulate whether the <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> will be used during the sale. She said the talks were about the amount of grain the Soviets could buy, not its price. The <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> was started four years ago to entice foreign buyers who were being lured away by countries that charged cheaper prices because of heavy government subsidies. Through the program, buyers are given bonus quantities of commodities if they buy a certain amount. The commodities come from the surplus stock purchased previously by the federal government from American farmers through other agricultural support programs. The fate of the <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> has been in question since April 18 when <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Kay </PERSON>, the foreign agriculture service administrator, told a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee that the agriculture department must hold all new <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> initiatives until the program had been reviewed by the <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says that under the program $ 8 billion in farm products have been sold, including wheat, wheat flour, vegetable oil, barley, barley malt, semolina, sorghum, rice, poultry feed, dairy cattle, eggs and frozen poultry. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> considers the program vital to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> strength during international trade negotiations, known as the <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Round </LOCATION>, which have been going on in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> position is that countries should remove or drastically reduce subsidies that distort world prices and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> believes that the <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> puts the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in a stronger bargaining position.
