<HEAD>Lorenzo Hanging Tough; Striking Eastern Employees Hanging On</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: ADDS final graf to UPDATE with Pritzker reportedly submitting
bid; No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As the strike gripping <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> approaches the end of its second month, boss <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> is hanging tough. After rejecting buyout proposals and producing his own plan to shrink the airline, <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> seems to be playing a waiting game with striking employees, who after nearly two months on the picket lines may be under increasing pressure to find jobs again. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> also must contend with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s creditors and with a federal bankruptcy judge, who must approve the downsizing plan and is pushing for a sale of Eastern in its entirety. `` It really continues to be a game of brinksmanship,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Decker </PERSON>, an airline industry analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Duff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Phelps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The strike has become the longest major walkout against a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airline since the industry was deregulated in October 1978. After a 17-month wage dispute, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s militant Machinists struck the Miami-based carrier on March 4 and were joined by pilots and flight attendants, virtually grounding the airline. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s parent <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, put <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> into Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection from creditors on March 9. Employees' hopes were stirred April 6 when a group led by ex-baseball commissioner <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> agreed to buy Eastern for $ 464 million. Hopes soared a few days later when the unions agreed to accept $ 210 million in wage concessions in exchange for a 30 percent stake in the carrier under the <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> deal. But the proposal collapsed over the unions' demand that a powerful trustee be appointed to replace <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> as head of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> before <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> took over _ a term the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> chief flatly rejected. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> now insists that a sale of Eastern in its entirety no longer is an option _ neither side will back down from their trustee positions _ although billionaire hotel executive <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Pritzker </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> and others have expressed buyout interest. Instead, the airline on Monday detailed plans to operate at one-third its pre-strike size and raise $ 1.8 billion by selling assets, including planes, airport gates and landing slots at unspecified locations. `` I think that was -LRB- <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>'s -RRB- intention all along,'' said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Geller </PERSON>, who follows the industry for <ORGANIZATION> Provident </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. As a first step, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> announced Thursday that it plans to lease 14 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727-200s to <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> for $ 96.6 million over five years, subject to bankruptcy court approval. Eastern is expected to announce more deals for leasing and selling aircraft in the coming days, according to sources close to the company. The plan is reminiscent of what <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> did with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s sister carrier <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> in September 1983 After he put <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> into Chapter 11, he slashed the number of employees to around 4,000 from 12,500 and brought the airline out of bankruptcy protection as a non-union carrier. Now, due to 1985 amendments to the bankruptcy laws, <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> would first have to negotiate further with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> unions and demonstrate that he had no alternative but to cut jobs. Some experts say <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>'s downsizing strategy could be aimed at luring back striking pilots, who would lose seniority if they took jobs at rival carriers. Under the plan, which would cut Eastern jobs from the pre-strike 31,200 to around 17,000, management reckons it would need about 1,700 pilots. The airline says it is hiring and training new pilots at the rate of around 200 a month. `` It's the airline version of voodoo economics,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Bavis </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s pilots union. `` And it's also designed to intimidate the 3,300 Eastern pilots into abandoning the picket line and returning to work.'' Some observers say it may be difficult for <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> to convince creditors and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Judge <PERSON> Burton </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> that the airline will be able to recruit 1,700 pilots in a reasonable period of time. <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Zweibel </PERSON>, the lead attorney for the committee representing <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s creditors, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> the panel would need about two weeks to form a judgment on <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s plan. There are still rumblings about a possible sale of the entire airline. <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> plans to hold a twice-postponed hearing next Wednesday on the issue of selling Eastern in its entirety, icluding its Northeast shuttle service the company already has agreed to sell to developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> for $ 365 million. Union officials and financial advisers continue to screen potential bidders for <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>; union sources said Thursday they have held discussions with five suitors they consider credible. The pilots union leadership told its members late Thursday that <PERSON> Pritzker </PERSON> has submitted his bid for the carrier and that <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> has requested confidential financial information from the bankruptcy court as a prelude to making his buyout offer.
