<SECOND>BC-Airlines-Future,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>America West Chief Paints Grim Picture of U.S. Air Industry Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Reregulation is a real prospect facing the domestic airline industry if current trends continue unabated, an airline executive warned. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON>, chairman of Phoenix-based <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, painted a generally grim picture of the industry's future, with fewer owners meaning lessened competition and higher fares <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Aviation-Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s annual news conference Thursday that deregulation initially created a highly competitive industry with low fares and a robust growth rate. But he said competitive balance has been destroyed by the concentration of ownership. In addition, he said, entry barriers to gaining a market share such as sophisticated computer reservation systems, access to restricted airports such as <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> LaGuardia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s National, and multibillion-dollar orders for new planes by the major airlines have made it even more difficult for the smaller carriers. `` If something is n't done, you've got an oligopoly with very high fares and little competition,'' <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> said. That could create `` a groundswell of public opinion that could mean the industry could experience reregulation,'' he said. `` If the barrier-to-entry problems are not resolved, that will happen.'' <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> said concern over the situation is starting to register in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, but that it will take such things as `` even higher prices, and they're going to get a lot higher, and several major failures,'' to bring concerted reform efforts. The ongoing problems of strikebound <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, including unsuccessful sale efforts amid Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization, are part of that, he added. `` It's riveting the attention of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on our industry right now,'' he said. <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> said he does not think the airline will fly again. `` I'm not sure Eastern can be successful as a smaller company,'' he said. Eastern's management recently proposed a plan to rebuild as a smaller carrier and sell around $ 1.8 billion in assets. As for his own 5-year-old airline, <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> said, `` We're not a buyer and we're not a seller. We certainly do n't think a hostile takeover would be possible. We're not a classic target.'' <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> posted a $ 10.07 million first-quarter profit on Wednesday, compared with a $ 16.32 million loss for the same period last year.
