<HEAD>Grain Prices Drop as Rains Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures opened lower today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> as a steady rain fell on areas of <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. The rain has given rise to sentiment that the drought that has plagued the area is over. `` We've had the best rain in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> in two years,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Frazier </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Balfour </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maclaine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` A lot of people are saying the drought is over, and that's what's been supporting us for a long time.'' Soybean prices also are being affected by word that a Brazilian dock strike is breaking up. Dockworkers gave their tentative approval to a court-ordered pay raise. Uncertainty over the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's position on continuing subsidized grain sales to foreign countries is putting pressure on wheat prices. In early trading, wheat was -RCB- cent to 1 -LCB- cents lower with the contract for delivery in May at $ 4.03 -LCB- a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 1 -LCB- cents lower with May at $ 2.67 -LCB- a bushel; oats were -LCB- cent to 3 \ cents lower with May at $ 1.74 a bushel; soybeans were 3 cents to 8 cents lower with May at $ 7.23 a bushel Cattle prices were higher on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in early trading, while pork prices were mostly lower. Live cattle were .15 cent to .38 cent higher with June at 71.20 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .50 cent to .80 cent higher with May at 76.25 cents a pound; hogs were .27 cent lower to .05 cent higher with June at 46.80 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .02 cent to .32 cent lower with May at 32.05 cents a pound. Livestock and meat futures settled mixed Thursday.
