<HEAD>Former Teamsters President Roy Williams Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 5 grafs of background. No pickup. Also moved on general
news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEETON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former Teamsters president <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> died today at his farm home after a lengthy bout with emphysema and heart problems. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, 73, was released from federal prison in September after serving three years of a 10-year sentence for attempting to bribe a senator over trucking legislation. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> served as international president of the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> union from 1981-83. He was forced to resign as <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> chief after he and four co-defendants were convicted in December 1982 for trying to bribe former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Cannon </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> to influence trucking deregulation. Cannon was not charged in the case. Though he maintained his innocence during the 1982 trial, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> acknowledged his role in the conspiracy case during testimony in 1985 in a <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> trial. He was cooperating with federal authorities investigating the mob in an attempt to have his own sentence reduced. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> testified that while he was a <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> labor leader before his elevation to the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> presidency, he had been under the control of <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Civella </PERSON>, the reputed crime boss in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> at the time. He said he received payoffs of $ 1,500 a month from <PERSON> Civella </PERSON> for seven years until he became Teamsters president. He said <PERSON> Civella </PERSON>, who has since died, played a key role in his election to the union presidency. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> also testified by videotape in a federal court trial in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> against mob fitures accused of fixing his election as <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> president, and that of his successor, <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Presser </PERSON>, who died last July. Three co-defendants were acquitted of that charge in May 1988, but convicted of unrelated charges.
