 It has targeted several segments of the market for further expansion, among them the prestige end of the fragrance and beauty aid business. Two years ago, <ORGANIZATION> Unilever </ORGANIZATION> bought <ORGANIZATION> Chesebrough-Pond </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 3.1 billion, thereby acquiring many widely known personal-care products, including several prestige, or expensive, lines such as the Prince <PERSON> Matchabelli </PERSON> fragrance collection. <ORGANIZATION> Unilever </ORGANIZATION> also owns <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>'s Passion scents. <PERSON> Lustig </PERSON> said the prestige portion of the personal products business appeals to <ORGANIZATION> Unilever </ORGANIZATION> because it has been growing strongly and has not been fully exploited, particularly in the Far East and other parts of the world. Prestige items account for an estimated $ 8 billion, or 20 percent, of the overall personal products market.
