<HEAD>Colt Firearms Up For Sale</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Colt Firearms, maker of the gun that won the West, was put on the auction block Friday, but the company's parent denied a three-year struggle with striking workers prompted the decision `` It's a going business and it's profitable, and, of course, it has a history of quality products,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Colt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Firearms </ORGANIZATION>' parent, <ORGANIZATION> Colt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> said senior officials at <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> decided to sell the firearms division so they could concentrate on the company's aerospace, automotive and industrial service operations A continuing strike and the recent loss of a contract to produce M-16 rifles for the military did n't prompt the action, he added. <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> declined to say whether privately held <ORGANIZATION> Colt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> had received any bids or how much the company is asking for the unit. <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has been hired to evaluate any offers. Analysts said proceeds from the sale could be used to help retire debt incurred when <ORGANIZATION> Colt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>' management mounted a $ 660 million leveraged buyout a year ago. <PERSON> Maeda </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>, a vice president with <ORGANIZATION> Donaldson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lufkin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Jenrette </PERSON>, estimated Colt's outstanding debt at $ 1.8 billion. The 1,100 employees at <ORGANIZATION> Colt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Firearms </ORGANIZATION>' two plants in <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> were informed of the decision Friday morning. `` I think it might be a good omen,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Madore </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Local </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 376 </ORGANIZATION>. The union represented about 1,000 blue-collar workers who walked off their jobs on Jan. 24, 1986, in a dispute over wages and benefits. `` I think maybe a new face, a new owner might turn it around,'' <PERSON> Madore </PERSON> said. He said the union could make an offer to buy the company, but he cautioned that such a move has n't yet been discussed with the membership. Colt has managed to keep its plants operating by hiring replacement workers and using about 200 strikers who crossed picket lines. The dispute is now before the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, where the union is seeking about $ 40 million in back wages and job reinstatement. <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> said a change in management could help end the walkout. `` Maybe there's an easy way out if you bring in a new company culture,'' she said. But State Rep. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Adamo </PERSON>, D-West Haven, said the sale could `` very well leave those -LRB- striking -RRB- workers in the lurch. It could be devastating.'' The Colt company was founded in <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> in 1836 by <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Colt </PERSON>, the inventor of the first successful repeating pistol. The pistol had a cylinder of several chambers that could be discharged in succession by the same locking and firing mechanism. It was after the entrepreneur's death in 1862 that his company manufactered the six-shooter that every cowboy carried in his holster and was said to have won the West. In addition to the M-16 rifle, the standard Army-issue rifle still used today, Colt manufactures the Colt 45 handgun, the King Cobra magnum revolver and the AR-15 rifle. Colt had produced the M-16 rifle for the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> since 1964. But in October 1988, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> announced that it was dropping Colt after it was underbid for a contract to produce about one million rifles by <ORGANIZATION> FN </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> FN </ORGANIZATION> manufacturing is owned by the Belgian firm, <ORGANIZATION> Fabrique </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S.A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colt </ORGANIZATION> gained national attention in March when it voluntarily decided to halt the sale of its semi-automatic rifles in response to public outcry to the murder of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> school-children by a man using a similar assault weapon.
