<HEAD>Shareholders Adopt Anti-Takeover Measures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> shareholders adopted measures Friday to fend off unwanted takeover bids and major stock acquisitions by foreigners, the company said. Mergers and other major stock purchases would have to be approved by holders of 80 percent of the media company's common stock, not including shares owned by the prospective buyer. An exemption could be made if the company's board, acting on a recommendation from a panel of independent journalism experts, backed the transaction. An 80 percent vote also would be needed to approve any stock purchase that would result in foreign ownership of more than 20 percent of the company. Actions by shareholders at the annual meeting were n't triggered by any actual efforts to buy company stock, said <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlatter </PERSON>. `` There have been no rumors and no activity whatsoever that we're aware of,'' she said. `` This really just has to do with the business climate that we exist in, in which business takeovers are becoming a part of our way of life.'' Shareholders also agreed to reserve an additional 3.5 million shares of common stock for the company's employee stock-option plan. <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> is an international communications company that publishes 30 daily newspapers and six suburban weeklies. The company has contracts to sell its eight television stations, the <LOCATION> Pasadena </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, Star-News and four smaller papers in the area. Negotiations also are under way to sell the <ORGANIZATION> Post-Tribune </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Gary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
