<HEAD>Dollar Rises Despite Intervention</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede: LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar rose sharply against all major currencies except the <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> dollar Friday despite central bank intervention and further indications that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy is losing steam. Gold prices took a tumble. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted a bid price for gold of $ 377.50 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from Thursday's late bid of $ 382.30. A <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report showing the government's chief economic forecasting gauge slipped 0.7 percent in March failed to halt the dollar's rise both at home and abroad. The drop in the index of leading indicators, which marked the first back-to-back declines in more than a year, was interpreted as another sign the economy is cooling, and analysts predicted the slowdown will become more pronounced later this year. Dealers also noted that coordinated central bank intervention, begun by the Swiss central bank and followed by the central banks of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, failed to stem the dollar's rise. `` The dollar has been firm all day; it's just ignoring the numbers,'' said <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Even though the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> appears unlikely to tighten credit by hiking interest rates, <PERSON> John