<HEAD>Upstart Diaper Company Taking On Big Competition</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bachelors <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pitassi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wally </PERSON> <PERSON> Klemp </PERSON> do n't have babies But they're covering the bottoms of infants with a disposable diaper they say is cheaper and better than the better-known competition. Move over Pampers, Luvs and Huggies, the diaper entrepreneurs say. Here come <ORGANIZATION> Drypers </ORGANIZATION>. The four-size, patent-pending diaper has what their company calls a `` double lock-away core'' that absorbs moisture and wicks it from the baby's skin. The core is made of paper fluff and two parallel bands of super-absorbent material that can soak up to 100 times its weight in liquid. Unlike the his-and-hers diapers that have a more absorbent material in the front and bottom, the Dryper core runs down the middle of the entire diaper, making it applicable for both girls and boys, <PERSON> Klemp </PERSON> says. `` We think our product has better features,'' says <PERSON> Pitassi </PERSON>. He and <PERSON> Klemp </PERSON> and a third partner, <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Tognietti </PERSON>, began marketing <ORGANIZATION> Drypers </ORGANIZATION> last summer, and they debuted on <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> grocery shelves in September. Sales are exceeding expectations, the company claims. It's reporting monthly sales of about $ 1 million and has captured 12 percent to 20 percent of the market in cities where Drypers are sold Although that's more than <PERSON> Veragon </PERSON> hoped for, it remains well below the dominance of <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, maker of Pampers and Luvs, and <ORGANIZATION> Kimberly-Clark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, maker of Huggies. So Veragon's founders are happy but reserved `` We do n't want to grow faster than we can control,'' <PERSON> Klemp </PERSON> says. Production at a new <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> plant already is running 24 hours a day, seven days a week to fill orders for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> and all of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The $ 3.3 billion national diaper business is not new to the Veragon partners. <PERSON> Pitassi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Klemp </PERSON>, both 30, formed a diaper company, <ORGANIZATION> VMG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION>, in <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, in 1984. `` I was working for <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Gamble selling diapers and saw the diaper business was growing. The country was going through a baby boom. It just represented a tremendous opportunity,'' <PERSON> Pitassi </PERSON> recalld. `` For us you had two big groups -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Gamble and <ORGANIZATION> Kimberly-Clark </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- and here we had come along with the same quality, if not better, diaper for a better price,'' he says. VMG, now the third-largest diaper maker, grossed millions months after production began. Within a year, however, the two lost control of the operation in a hostile takeover. They ventured out on their own again. <PERSON> Tognietti </PERSON>, 31, learned the diaper business during nine years with <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION> _ which introduced disposable diapers in 1961 with Pampers _ and helped design P & amp; G's gender-specialized Luvs diapers. Cincinnati-based <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Gamble is the nation's largest producer of disposable diapers, claiming 47 percent of market. Dallas-based <ORGANIZATION> Kimberly-Clark </ORGANIZATION> is No. 2 with about 30 percent. The top two are locked in a court battle. <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION> is suing its main competitor for patent infringement, accusing <ORGANIZATION> Kimberly-Clark </ORGANIZATION> of copying the design of its highly successful super-absorbent Pampers for use in super-absorbent Huggies. <PERSON> Pitassi </PERSON> says selling <ORGANIZATION> Drypers </ORGANIZATION> close to the factory saves the company transportation costs and enables Veragon to charge an average of $ 1 less per box of diapers than the competition. Veragon picked <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> as its manufacturing center over six other <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> cities, partly because of tax abatements and ardent wooing by the <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. The heart of the company's 80,500-square-foot headquarters is a $ 2 million diaper-assembly machine that combines 15 raw materials. The machine, dubbed `` Drypers One'' churns out 350 diapers a minute. The company eventually may diversify and produce other paper products, but for now, <ORGANIZATION> Drypers </ORGANIZATION> is the main focus. `` No question _ our baby is <ORGANIZATION> Drypers </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Klemp </PERSON> says.
