<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     04-28 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bond prices fell Friday despite economic statistics indicating that the economy is cooling and interest rates may ease. The credit market's bellwether 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> issue was down -LRB- point, or $ 1.25 for every $ 1,000 face amount. Its yield, which moves inversely to price, rose to 8.92 percent from 8.90 percent late Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said its chief economic forecasting gauge plunged 0.7 percent in March, the second straight decline and the biggest drop in eight months. It was the first time the Index of Leading Economic Indicators, which dropped 0.3 percent in February, posted back-to-back declines since it fell for five straight months from September 1987 through January 1988. Analysts said the 30-year bond gained slightly after the economic data was announced, but the gains dwindled throughout the day. `` After the run we've had this week, I think investors were saying perhaps it's time to take a breather,'' said <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON>, a portfolio manager with <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. `` I think we will need some further signs of moderating inflation and economic growth before we get any further significant rally,'' he said. Bond traders used the opportunity to take profits following a runup in the previous session, analysts said. The 30-year bond rose -LCB- point Thursday. Analysts said the latest negative signals are in line with signs that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy is losing steam. The prospects of slower growth `` is appeasing the market for now,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Mitchell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Held </ORGANIZATION>, chief financial economist at <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. In the secondary market for <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities, prices of short-term securities were down from 1-16 point to 5-32 point, intermediate governments fell 3-32 point to 7-32 point and long-term maturities slumped from -LRB- point to 3-16 point, according to <ORGANIZATION> Telerate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a financial information service. The movement of a point equals a change of $ 10 in the price of a bond with a $ 1,000 face value. The <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Bond Index, which measures price movements on all outstanding <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> issues with maturities of a year or longer, fell 2.06 to 1,132.74. Corporate issues advanced. <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return on a portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, rose 0.41 to 304.49. The Bond Buyer index was unavailable. Yields on three-month <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills leaped to 8.78 percent as the discount rose 13 basis points to 8.49 percent. Yields on six-month bills rose to 9.05 percent as the discount rose 9 basis points to 8.55 percent. Yields on one-year bills rose to 9.19 percent as the discount gained 10 basis points to 8.51 percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield is the annualized return on an investment in a <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bill. The discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face value, paid at maturity. The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, traded at 913-16 percent, unchanged from late Thursday.
