<HEAD>Is There A Stroh-Heileman Beer In The Future?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heileman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> officials have discussed buying a minority interest in the <ORGANIZATION> Stroh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, touching off speculation about a possible merger between two of the nation's largest beer companies. But analysts question whether such a deal could clear federal antitrust laws. <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> officials several weeks ago announced their willingness to sell a minority interest in the Detroit-based company, the third-largest brewer in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The speculation about a merger was touched off when <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> <PERSON> Cutbush </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer of La Crosse-based <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON>, disclosed Thursday that representatives from his company were in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> to meet with <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> officials. <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON>, which was bought by <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Bond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in 1987, is the nation's No. 5 brewer, with a 1988 estimate of 15.4 million barrels. <PERSON> Lacey </PERSON> <PERSON> Logan </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Stroh </LOCATION> spokeswoman, said Friday that <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> `` is in the process of finding an international minority investment partner or partners'' for `` opportunities available to <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> outside of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' She said that <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> `` has been having ongoing meetings with a number of international brewers.'' <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> shipped an estimated 20.6 million barrels in 1988, far behind the 40.5 million shipped by the <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which is the country's second largest brewer. <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION>. Inc. was No 1 with a 1988 estimate of 78.5 million barrels. Industry analysts have predicted competitors of <PERSON> Anheuser </PERSON> and <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> might need to consolidate in order to challenge the companies on a national level. `` <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> and <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON> would be a sensible merger,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberg </PERSON>, an industry analyst and professor of marketing management at <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. `` <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON> has a lot of volume, but not good infrastructure,'' he said. `` <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> has good infrastructure, but they do n't have a lot of volume.'' `` You're looking at creating a brewer the approximate size of <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>,'' he said. One major obstacle, however, could be antitrust laws, which blocked earlier attempts by <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON> to buy both the <PERSON> Jos </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Schlitz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Pabst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Schlitz </PERSON> was later bought by <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> `` If I were a smaller company, I would be squealing like a pig,'' <PERSON> Weinberg </PERSON> said. If such a merger were proposed, he said, a critical issue would be whether the combination of <LOCATION> Stroh </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON> would increase competition within the industry or reduce it. In his remarks Thursday to the <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wholesale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Distributors </ORGA