<HEAD>Precious Metals Prices Drop On Signs Of Slowing Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Precious metals prices dropped sharply Friday as evidence of a slowing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy continued to mount. The decline was led by gold, which tumbled on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> to a new low for the May contract On other markets, wheat prices rose while corn and soybean prices fell; cattle prices rallied but hog prices retreated; and energy prices were mixed. Gold settled $ 5.40 to $ 6.20 lower with the contract for delivery in May at $ 377.90 a troy ounce; silver was 4.4 cents to 7 cents lower with May at $ 5.601 a troy ounce; platinum settled at $ 21.70 to $ 17.70 lower with July at $ 534.50 a troy ounce. The sell-off was largely a response to the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s report Friday that the index of leading economic indicators plunged 0.7 percent in March It was the second consecutive decline in the index and the sharpest in eight months. Precious metals, especially gold, are traditionally seen as safe investments during periods of rising inflation. An economic slowdown would likely result in less inflation. Platinum prices had risen sharply earlier in the week and although supply factors are bullish, `` there is a lot of uncertainty in the amount of demand,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Anagnos </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Thomson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McKinnon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Analysts attributed the drop in silver prices to the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s report of a relatively large amount of the metal _ 200 million ounces _ in exchange-approved warehouses The stockpile equals about 20 months of demand, <PERSON> Anagnos </PERSON> said. Wheat closed sharply higher on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ