<HEAD>Midwest Exchange Plans Evening Session</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Midwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, in an attempt to capture a share of the after-hours trading of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stocks, is proposing a second computerized trading session, officials said Thursday. The new trading session, from 3:30 p.m. to 5 p.m. CDT, would be for the trading of portfolios and not for individual customers, said vice president <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendrick </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> exchange is currently open from 8:30 a.m. to 3 p.m. CDT. Most of the stocks traded on the exchange are also traded on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The exchange applied Wednesday to the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> for approval. <PERSON> Hendrick </PERSON> estimated that stock portfolios traded after hours equal 10 million to 20 million shares daily. But the activity is not reflected in reported trading volume and the volume is difficult to accurately measure. <PERSON> Hendrick </PERSON> said the portfolios traded in the late afternoon will be required to consist of at least 20 stocks, none of which may be greater than 10 percent of the value of the portfolio. Brokerage firms trading portfolios will send their transactions electronically into a computer at the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> exchange, which will record the trade. Currently, such trades are registered on the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> to comply with <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> rules that member brokerages trade on recognized