<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three months after a federal appeals court ruled that <ORGANIZATION> Steelcase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> violated patents held by <ORGANIZATION> Haworth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the office furniture giant has turned the tables. <ORGANIZATION> Steelcase </ORGANIZATION> filed a lawsuit Wednesday in federal court contending the smaller Holland-based company has infringed on two <ORGANIZATION> Steelcase </ORGANIZATION> patents, one granted in 1980 and the second in 1984. Both are for panel electrical wiring systems, according to the lawsuit. <ORGANIZATION> Steelcase </ORGANIZATION> insists the lawsuit is neither related to nor in retaliation for an earlier one filed by <PERSON> Haworth </PERSON> now before the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. While both lawsuits involve the electrical system in the two companies' panel systems, <ORGANIZATION> Steelcase </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> said: `` They're different patents and different issues. ... It's the same church, but it's a different pew.'' <PERSON> Haworth </PERSON>, the nation's third-largest office furniture maker, sued <ORGANIZATION> Steelcase </ORGANIZATION> in 1985, claiming the industry leader was infringing on <PERSON> Haworth </PERSON> patents when it designed, made and sold certain pre-wired office panels. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Enslen </PERSON> last year ruled in favor of <ORGANIZATION> Steelcase </ORGANIZATION>, but a federal appeals court reversed that opinion in January, ruling for <PERSON> Haworth </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Steelcase </ORGANIZATION> appealed to the nation's highest court <ORGANIZATION> Steelcase </ORGANIZATION> could end up paying hundreds of millions of dollars to <PERSON> Haworth </PERSON> if the ruling stands. <PERSON> Haworth </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Planck </PERSON> said Thursday the company would have no comment until it receives formal notification of the lawsuit.
