<HEAD>MAI Basic Earnings Drop 61.8 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUSTIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> MAI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Basic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Four </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which designs and makes business computers, said Friday that earnings dropped nearly 62 percent in the first three months of 1989 due in part to efforts to acquire Prime Computer. Other factors contributing to the decline were a slowdown in the mid-range computer industry and a softened dollar overseas, the company said. Earnings for the second quarter ended March 31 declined to $ 2.4 million, or 16 cents per share, from $ 6.3 million, or 42 cents per share, for the same quarter last year. `` Although our period earnings declined compared to last year, through prudent expense controls we were able to achieve an operating income margin of 12.8 percent for the six months ended March 31, 1989, an excellent result in the context of the current industry-wide slowdown,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patton </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer. Revenue for the quarter declined from $ 105.4 million in 1988 to $ 104.7 million this year, the company said. The company said Prime Computer's resistance to a MAI tender offer made last year contributed to the earnings decline. It noted that the <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has set a May 24 hearing on company motions to invalidate Prime's takeover defense. `` MBF remains committed to acquiring Prime at the earliest possible time,'' said company Chairman <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> LeBow </PERSON>. Orders for company products declined 5 percent in the first six months of the company's fiscal year, compared to the same period a year ago, primarily because of lower European sales, <PERSON> Patton </PERSON> said. MAI Basic Four designs, manufacturers and markets mid-range business computers and information processing systems for multi-user applications worldwide. The company, which has 4,200 employees, markets products in 39 countries.
